{This lecture covers Modern Benoni and Czech Benoni. Even though these openings are considered risky at the top-level, every tournament player should be very well prepared with White. This lecture, will provide you with easy-to-learn and very practical repertoire for White. As usual, knowing plans and ideas will be more important than memorization of concrete theory.}  *

[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Modern Benoni"]
[Black "Theory & Plans"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[ECO "A61"]
[EventDate "2013.11.08"]
[PlyCount "31"]
[SourceVersionDate "2024.02.19"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 { We don't capture with the knight because trading pieces is not our forte. It's Black's dream to trade minor pieces. } 5... d6 6. Nf3 g6 { There are other ways like Nbd7 but it usually transposes. } 7. Bf4 { We are targeting Black's weakness on d6. } 7... a6 $5 { planning b5. } ( 7... Bg7 $5 { is not the same as 7...a6. Black's idea is to castle fast, and put the knight on a6! ....we will avoid the more common 8. Qa4+, which has a lot of concrete theory, and instead we will play the equally good 8.h3! ..which may transpose at any moment to the a6-a4 system... or it may have just a bit of independent theory if blackheads for the Na6 plan } 8. h3 $1 { stopping Bg4-Bxf3 ideas. } ( 8. Qa4+ $1 { main line with a lot of theory. } 8... Bd7 9. Qb3 ) 8... O-O $1 ( 8... b5 $6 { rare & dubious but proper knowledge is required. } 9. Nxb5 $1 Qa5+ 10. Nc3 Ne4 { Black is threatening to capture on c3 and we have two options Nd2 and Rc1. The former is the simplest. } 11. Nd2 $16 Nxc3 12. bxc3 O-O 13. e3 Bxc3 14. Rc1 Re8 15. Be2 Ba6 16. Rc2 Bxe2 17. Qxe2 { with castling to follow up, we have no problems whatsoever. } ) 9. e3 Na6 $5 { planning Nc7-b5. } ( 9... a6 10. a4 { will transpose to the other mainline with 7...a6 } ) 10. Bxa6 $1 { a very simple and effective move. This is usually not so good in Benoni, but things here are a little more concrete. } 10... bxa6 11. Rc1 $3 { Make sure to play Rc1 quickly so that we can play b3 whenever necessary. } ( 11. O-O $2 { Make sure you don't fall into this trap. } 11... Rb8 $1 12. Qe2 Re8 $13 { when things are very unclear and probably worse for White. } ) 11... Rb8 ( 11... Bf5 12. O-O $16 { Simple. Black has no counterplay. } 12... Ne4 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Ng5 Bf5 15. e4 Bc8 16. b3 $16 { Black's play doesn't make sense. White has a clear advantage. } ) 12. b3 a5 { Black is being tricky with a dirty threat of Ba6 to stop our castling, but of course, it's our move now. } 13. O-O Ba6 14. Re1 Re8 15. e4 $16 { Our next plan is to go for e4-e5 at a good moment. Make sure to study the model games. } ) 8. a4 { stopping b5. } 8... Bg7 { In Benoni structures, Black always aims to trade one pair of minor pieces usually with Bg4-Bxf3. As he lacks space trading pieces makes complete sense, so we will always stop Bg4 ideas with h3. } 9. h3 $1 { stopping Bg4. } 9... O-O 10. e3 { We plan to first develop our pieces and castle and later think about e3-e4. } 10... Re8 { Now, Ne4 is a real threat. } ( 10... Qb6 $2 { This is completely meaningless. } 11. Qc1 $16 { White will next play Nd2 and Nc4 comes up with a free tempo for us. } ) ( 10... Qe7 $5 { Supporting d6 pawn thus planning Nbd7. } 11. Be2 Nbd7 ( 11... Ne4 $2 { This is premature, Black should instead focus on development. } 12. Nxe4 Qxe4 13. Nd2 $16 { very important move to be memorized. } ) 12. Nd2 $1 { This is also good and no theory is needed anymore. It's just plans once again! } ) ( 10... Nh5 $2 { This move planning f5-f4 doesn't work well for Black because he is underdeveloped. } 11. Bh2 $16 f5 12. Be2 f4 $2 13. O-O $3 fxe3 ( 13... Nd7 14. Nd2 $18 fxe3 15. fxe3 Rxf1+ 16. Qxf1 { This is plane horrible for Black, the h5-knight is simply placed and the other pieces are underdeveloped. } ) 14. fxe3 $18 { White is winning. Such positions can be played even without a pawn, and we often leave the e3-pawn for initiative. } ) 11. Bd3 $1 ( 11. Nd2 $1 { this is also very good. Once again concrete theory would be a waste of time here. Just study some typical ideas that follow! } ) 11... Nbd7 12. O-O ( 12. Bxd6 $6 { Usually this capture doesn't work 90% of the time and we don't wish to memorize the rest 10% of the cases, where it works because we might confuse things together. So, just remember the ideas not moves! } ) 12... Nh5 13. Bh2 $1 { We don't have to remember the best move Bxd6 here, instead Bh2 is simple enough. } 13... Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 16. Qd2 $16 { Black has managed to exchange some minor pieces, but to do so, he misplaced the rest of his pieces. White has a clear advantage } *[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
