1. d4 c5 { This is the so called Czech Benoni. A playable but passive opening. Black plans for the f7-f5 break after closing the center with c5 and e5, but we will not allow that. } ( 1... Nf6 { Black can also start with this moveoder. } 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e5 4. Nc3 d6 5. e4 { The main structure of Czech Benoni. } 5... Be7 6. h3 O-O 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. Bd3 Ne8 9. g4 { The most effective way to stop f7-f5. } 9... a6 10. a4 b6 11. Be3 Rb8 12. Qe2 g6 13. Kd1 $3 Ng7 14. Rg1 Nf6 15. Kc2 $16 { Black has no active plan. And White will slowly build his attack on the Kingside! } ) 2. d5 d6 3. c4 e5 4. e4 Be7 ( 4... f5 { This is horrible. } 5. exf5 Bxf5 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Nge2 { planning Ng3, Bd3 and once the Bishop's are traded it's game over. } 7... Be7 8. Ng3 Bg6 9. h4 { with clear advantage. } ) 5. Nf3 Nf6 6. Nc3 O-O 7. h3 { planning g4 to stop g6-f5. } 7... a6 8. a4 Ne8 9. g4 ( 9. Bd3 { simply allows } 9... f5 10. exf5 Bxf5 11. Bxf5 Rxf5 { which is not needed. } ) 9... Nd7 10. Bd3 g6 11. Be3 Ng7 12. Qe2 Nf6 { Black is eyeing the g4-pawn in order to avoid h4-h5 pretty soon, but we can delay that plan and focus on the other side. } 13. Kd1 $3 Bd7 14. Kc2 $16 { The c2-square is reserved for us in this line. After that, we will slowly but surely, build our Kingside attack. } *[Event "?"]
