1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 { This is the Benko Gambit. Black wants to open the a- and b-file and play on the Queenside. } 4. cxb5 a6 5. b6 $5 { We immediately return the pawn and get a pleasant position! } ( 5. bxa6 { may be objectively best but it gives Black counterplay. } ) *[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.02.15"]
[Round "?"]
[White "BENKO GAMBIT"]
[Black "THEORETICAL OVERVIEW"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[ECO "A57"]
[EventDate "2024.02.15"]
[PlyCount "37"]
[Source "ChessBase"]
[SourceDate "1994.03.01"]
[SourceQuality "1"]
[SourceVersion "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "1994.03.01"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. b6 $1 e6 $1 { This is the critical test! Will we be able to put Black under pressure? } ( 5... g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. e4 { transposes to 5...d6. } ) ( 5... d6 $6 { One of the big advantages of the b6 Benko is that all these typical strategies in the style of the ba6 Benko do not work at all for Black! His position, with only one open file on the Queenside and not two, is much less dynamic. White can with simple typical moves get a good advantage! Nevertheless, many players will the black pieces will play this way - SO BE PREPARED! } 6. Nc3 Qxb6 ( 6... g6 { This is very similar to 6...Qxb6. } 7. e4 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. a4 ( 9. Qb3 $5 { Even this rare move seems to pose some problems for Black, but there are simpler ways! } 9... Bb7 10. Bd3 ( 10. Nd2 Nbd7 11. Nc4 a5 12. a4 Ng4 13. h4 $5 h5 ( 13... Bd4 14. f3 $16 ) 14. Bg5 Bd4 15. f3 $16 ) 10... Nbd7 11. Na4 Rb8 12. Bd2 $16 ) 9... a5 10. Bb5 $1 ( 10. Be2 $14 ) 10... Nbd7 11. O-O Nxb6 12. Bf4 $16 ( 12. Re1 $16 Bg4 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 $16 Nfd7 ( 14... Ne8 15. Qe2 $18 ( 15. Bg5 $16 ) 15... Nc7 16. Bc6 Rb8 17. Bg5 $16 Nd7 18. Bb5 Nxb5 19. Nxb5 Rb7 20. Rac1 Nb8 21. b3 $16 { White has a strategically winning position. For instance } 21... Na6 22. Bd2 Nb4 23. f4 Qd7 24. Qc4 Re8 25. Rcd1 Rbb8 26. Bc3 $18 ( 26. Kh1 $18 ) ) 15. Qe2 $16 c4 16. Be3 ) ( 12. h3 $16 ) 12... Ne8 13. Re1 Nc7 14. e5 $16 ) 7. e4 g6 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. Nd2 $1 ( 9. a4 Bg4 $5 ) ( 9. Be2 $1 Bg4 10. Nd2 ) 9... O-O 10. a4 $1 { Now Black has two strategies: - playing ...a6-a5 himself - or allowing White to play a5 In my view, the best for Black is the second one: However, in both cases, White is better! . And once again, only the typical plans matter, not the concrete theory! } ( 10. Nc4 $1 { This idea by the great former World Champion Anatoly Karpov, is a bit different but also very effective! } 10... Qc7 11. Be2 Nbd7 12. Bf4 $1 { The bishop is safe on f4 (no ... Nh5 ideas) and White wants to avoid the knight exchange after ...Nb6 on the next move by Ne3. Taking on b6 would give black very easy play here! The knight on b6 will turn out to be very misplaced! } 12... Nb6 13. Ne3 $1 Nfd7 ( 13... a5 $5 14. a4 c4 $14 ) 14. Rc1 $16 { --> model game Karpov-Belotti } ( 14. h4 $16 { A bit risky for my taste but objectively also good! } 14... Ne5 ( 14... h5 15. g4 $16 ) 15. h5 $36 ) ) 10... a5 ( 10... Nbd7 11. a5 Qc7 12. Be2 { Now, quite often we plan to play Nc4-Na4 and to put a knight on b6! There follow some sample lines: } 12... Rb8 ( 12... Bb7 $2 13. Nc4 $16 ) 13. O-O Ne8 ( 13... Rb4 14. Nc4 Bb7 15. Bd2 $16 ( 15. h3 $16 ) ( 15. Bf4 $16 ) ) 14. Re1 $1 ( 14. Nc4 $1 Ne5 15. Ne3 $14 ( 15. Nb6 Nd7 16. Nca4 Nxb6 17. Nxb6 $14 ) ) 14... Qd8 15. Nc4 Ne5 16. Nb6 ( 16. Ne3 ) 16... Nc7 17. Nca4 $1 { even after allowing the black knight to go to d4..white is better ! } 17... Nb5 18. Be3 Nd4 19. h3 ( 19. Bf1 $4 Bg4 $17 ) ( 19. Bxd4 cxd4 20. Nxc8 Qxc8 21. Nb6 Qb7 22. Rc1 $16 ) 19... Nd7 20. Bd3 $16 ) 11. Bb5 $1 { REMEMBER: WHEN THE MOVE Bb5 IS POSSIBLE, WE MUST PLAY IT - IT IS USUALLY THE BEST! } 11... Ba6 12. Nc4 Qd8 13. O-O $16 { Some sample lines to illustrate ideas: } 13... Nbd7 ( 13... Bxb5 14. axb5 $16 ( 14. Nxb5 Nxe4 ) ) 14. Qe2 $16 ( 14. Bg5 $16 ) ( 14. Re1 Bxb5 15. axb5 $16 ( 15. Nxb5 $16 Nb6 16. Nxb6 Qxb6 17. Rb1 Ne8 18. b3 Nc7 19. Na3 $16 Na6 20. Nc4 Qc7 21. Bb2 $16 ( 21. Bf4 $16 Nb4 22. Qd2 { The black knight is very misplaced on b4! } ) ) ) 14... Ne8 15. Bxa6 Rxa6 16. Bg5 Nc7 17. Rac1 $16 { OUR PLAN IS TO BLOCK THE Queenside AND THEN SLOWLY START ATTACKING ON THE Kingside! } 17... Ra8 18. f4 $16 ( 18. Nxd6 $4 f6 ) 18... Na6 19. Nb5 $18 Nb4 20. f5 $1 Ne5 21. b3 Nxc4 22. bxc4 Be5 23. Bh6 $18 ( 23. Qg4 ) ( 23. Rf3 $18 ) ) 6. Nc3 Nxd5 { The most common and most accurate! Black shouldn't White allow to play e4. } ( 6... exd5 7. Nxd5 { this just transposes to our main line. } ( 7. Bg5 $36 { is an interesting extra option that White does not have after 6...Nxd5. } ) ) ( 6... Bb7 $6 7. e4 exd5 8. exd5 Qxb6 ( 8... d6 9. a4 $1 { is the engine's top choice! } 9... Qxb6 ( 9... a5 10. Bb5+ $16 Nbd7 11. Nge2 $16 ( 11. g4 $18 h6 12. h4 Qxb6 13. Rh3 $3 O-O-O 14. g5 $16 ) ) 10. a5 Qd8 11. Nf3 Be7 12. Bc4 O-O 13. O-O Nbd7 14. Re1 Re8 15. h3 $16 ( 15. Bf4 $16 ) ) 9. Nf3 d6 { Black is not in time to play ...g6 and ...Bg7. } ( 9... g6 10. Qe2+ ( { or } 10. Bc4 Bg7 11. Qe2+ ) ) 10. Bc4 Be7 11. O-O $16 { White gets the advantage with simple moves - Black suffers from a lack of space. } ) ( 6... Qxb6 7. e4 exd5 8. exd5 d6 9. Nf3 Be7 { Unfortunately for black , he doesn't have enough time to put his bishop on g7 because he will lose his castling rights! } ( 9... g6 $2 10. Nd2 Bg7 11. Qe2+ Kf8 12. Nc4 $16 ) 10. Nd2 ( 10. Bd3 Bg4 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nbd7 13. Bc2 O-O 14. O-O Ne5 15. Qe2 $14 ) 10... O-O 11. Bd3 Nbd7 12. Nc4 Qd8 13. Bf4 Nb6 14. Ne3 $14 ) 7. Nxd5 exd5 8. Qxd5 Nc6 9. Nf3 $1 Rb8 $1 { This is the only good move! } ( 9... Be7 $2 { is a big mistake as this allows } 10. Ne5 $3 O-O 11. Nxc6 dxc6 12. Qxd8 $1 { White can rely on his long-term plus - the much better pawn structure. } ( { We should not take } 12. Qxc6 { as Black has an advantage in development. } ) 12... Bxd8 { After this we need to know a little bit of theory - we just want to stabilize the position! } ( 12... Rxd8 $2 { Now Black does not get the b6 pawn. } 13. Bf4 $1 Bf6 14. Rd1 $3 Rd4 15. Rxd4 $3 ( 15. e3 $16 ) 15... cxd4 16. g3 $3 Bd8 17. Bg2 $18 Bb7 18. Bc7 ) 13. e3 { We want to put our bishops on c4 and c3. } 13... Bxb6 ( { If Black prevents Bc4 with } 13... Be6 { , we have } 14. b7 $18 { [%csl Ra6,Gb7] } ) 14. Bc4 $1 Rd8 ( { or } 14... Ba5+ 15. Bd2 Bxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Rd8+ 17. Kc3 $16 { White will play Rd1 and possibly prepare Kc4, starting to collect Black's pawns. } ) 15. Bd2 $16 { with a huge advantage in the endgame. } ) ( 9... Qf6 $6 10. e4 $16 Bb7 11. Bd3 ( 11. Bc4 ) 11... Rb8 12. Qb3 $16 ) 10. e4 $1 Be7 $1 ( 10... Qxb6 $2 11. Bc4 $1 { Now Black needs to misplace his knight in order to defend f7. } 11... Nd8 12. O-O Ne6 13. Bg5 $16 ( 13. Bf4 $16 ) ( 13. b3 $16 ) ) ( 10... Rxb6 $2 { is also bad as here Black needs to misplace his queen: } 11. Bc4 Qf6 12. O-O $16 Be7 13. Bg5 Qe6 14. Qd3 ) 11. Bc4 O-O 12. O-O $1 { There are some other tries as well, but this seems to be the best. } ( 12. Bd2 $5 Qxb6 ( 12... Rxb6 13. Bc3 d6 14. O-O Be6 15. Qd3 Bxc4 16. Qxc4 Bf6 17. Rad1 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 $14 ) 13. Bc3 d6 14. O-O Be6 15. Qd3 Bxc4 16. Qxc4 Qb5 17. Qd5 $14 { the computer call it equal . .but white is a bit better in a practical sence } ) ( 12. Qh5 d6 13. h4 $5 { This risky line is for those who want to play a very sharp game! } 13... Rxb6 $2 { loses immediately to } 14. Ng5 $18 { [%csl Rf7,Rh7][%cal Yg5f7,Yg5h7,Yc4f7] } ) 12... Rxb6 ( 12... Qxb6 $6 13. e5 $14 ( 13. Ng5 $14 Nd8 14. Qf5 Bxg5 15. Qxg5 Ne6 16. Qg3 $16 ) ) ( 12... Na5 $6 { This has been played a few times but it doesn't seem to be good. } 13. Bd3 $1 Rxb6 14. Qh5 $14 ( 14. Bd2 $14 Nc6 15. Qh5 d6 16. b3 Bf6 17. Rad1 $14 ) 14... d6 ( 14... Bb7 15. Bd2 Rd6 16. Rad1 $16 ( 16. Bc2 $14 Nc4 17. Bc3 Rh6 18. Qg4 Rg6 19. Qf4 $14 ) 16... Nc6 17. Bc4 $16 ) 15. b3 Bf6 16. Bd2 $1 Nc6 17. Rad1 $14 ) ( 12... Bb7 $2 13. Qh5 $16 ( 13. Qf5 $16 ) ) 13. Bd2 $1 ( 13. Ng5 $5 { This is also interesting: } 13... Qe8 $1 ( 13... Bxg5 $4 14. Bxg5 Qc7 15. Qxc5 $18 ) 14. Qf5 $1 g6 $6 ( 14... Bxg5 $1 15. Qxg5 d6 ( 15... Qxe4 $2 16. Qxc5 $16 ) 16. Bd3 $14 ) 15. Qh3 h5 16. Qg3 Nd4 17. Bd2 $14 Rxb2 $4 18. Nxf7 Ne2+ 19. Bxe2 Qxf7 20. Bc4 $18 Qxc4 21. Qxg6+ Kh8 22. Qxh5+ Kg8 23. Qg6+ Kh8 24. Rac1 Rc2 25. Rxc2 Qxc2 26. Bh6 Rg8 27. Qh5 $18 { This is a line given by the computer. } ) 13... d6 ( 13... Rxb2 $6 { This is risky, although it is not losing by force! } 14. Bc3 Rb6 15. Qh5 $16 { A typical attacking idea in these lines - the absence of a knight on f6 is felt! } ( 15. Rad1 $14 ) 15... d6 16. Rad1 { White has a strong initiative, for example } 16... Be6 { loses a pawn to } ( 16... Bf6 17. e5 ) 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. Qg4 e5 19. Nxe5 $16 ) 14. Bc3 { The good thing about these positions is that we can count on a small risk-free advantage in some middlegame or endgame! } 14... Be6 ( 14... Bg4 15. Qd3 $14 ) ( 14... Bf6 $5 15. Qd3 $1 Bxc3 16. bxc3 $14 { This time we take with the pawn because ...Bg4-Bxf3 is coming and we need to stop ...Nd4! } 16... Bg4 17. Bb3 Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Ne5 19. Qe2 $14 ) 15. Qd3 Bxc4 ( 15... Nb4 16. Qe2 Bxc4 17. Qxc4 $14 ) 16. Qxc4 Bf6 17. Rad1 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 Qe7 19. Rfe1 $14 { White has a small and risk-free advantage! Very far from the dynamic play Black was aiming for when going for the Benko Gambit! } *[Event "?"]

