1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. b6 d6 6. Nc3 Qxb6 7. e4 g6 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. Nd2 $1 O-O 10. Nc4 $1 { This idea by the great former World Champion Anatoly Karpov, is a bit different but also very effective! } ( 10. a4 $1 ) 10... Qc7 11. Be2 Nbd7 12. Bf4 $1 { The bishop is safe on f4 (no ...Nh5 ideas) and White wants to avoid the knight exchange after ...Nb6 on the next move by Ne3. Taking on b6 would give black very easy play here! The knight on b6 will turn out to be very misplaced! } 12... Nb6 13. Ne3 $1 Nfd7 ( 13... a5 $5 14. a4 c4 $14 ) 14. Rc1 $16 ( 14. h4 $16 { A bit risky for my taste but objectively also good! } 14... h5 ( 14... Ne5 15. h5 ) 15. g4 $3 ) 14... a5 15. a4 Nb8 16. Nb5 Qd8 17. b3 Na6 18. O-O Nb4 19. Qd2 Ba6 20. Rfd1 Nd7 21. f3 Nf6 22. Bc4 $16 { Karpov perfectly executed the typical strategy of first blocking the Queenside and then start attacking on the Kingside! This game is a piece of art! } 22... Ne8 23. Re1 Nc7 24. Na3 Qd7 ( 24... Bxc4 25. Naxc4 Re8 26. Ng4 Qb8 27. Nh6+ Kf8 28. Bg5 $18 ) 25. Kh1 Bd4 26. Bh6 Rfb8 27. Ng4 Bxc4 28. Nxc4 Ne8 29. Be3 Bxe3 30. Rxe3 Nf6 31. Nf2 $18 ( 31. Nxf6+ exf6 32. Rce1 $18 ) 31... Qd8 32. Rce1 Qf8 33. f4 Qg7 34. Rd1 Nh5 35. Nh3 Nf6 36. Qe2 Qh6 37. Rf3 Qh5 38. Nf2 Qh6 39. g3 Qg7 40. Kg2 h5 41. Nh3 Rd8 42. Ng5 Nh7 43. Nxh7 Kxh7 44. f5 f6 45. fxg6+ Kxg6 46. Rf5 Rh8 47. Rdf1 Rh6 48. e5 dxe5 49. Rxe5 Ra7 50. d6 1-0[Event "ch-Central Serbia w 2012"]
