{ A perfect example of the typical strategy: first White manages to block the Queenside and then, slowly prepares an an attack on the Kingside! } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 { This can lead to our variation by transposition. With this move order White avoids the variation 4.cxb5 a6 5.b6 e6. } 4... g6 ( { However the aditional possibility } 4... b4 { is possible. } ) 5. cxb5 a6 6. b6 { Now we have transposed to our system. } 6... d6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. e4 Bg7 9. a4 a5 10. Bb5 $1 { The rule is that whenever Bb5 is possible (in one go, not Be2-Bb5) then we must play it! b5 is the best square for our bishop, and whenever black plays .. .Ba6-Bxb5, both, ab5 and Nxb5 can be good for White - depending on the position of course. } 10... O-O 11. O-O Nxb6 12. Bf4 $14 ( 12. h3 $14 ) ( 12. Re1 $14 { We look at a very nice sample line to show once again the typical plans! } 12... Bg4 { This exchange will not save Black - this is a Benko, not a Benoni! } 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 $16 Ne8 15. Bg5 Nc7 16. Bc6 Rb8 17. Qe2 { Stopping ...Nc4. } 17... Kh8 18. Rac1 $1 { Getting ready to play b3 and start blocking the queeside! It is hard to even suggest a move for Black now! } 18... Nd7 19. Nb5 ( 19. b3 ) 19... Nxb5 20. Bxb5 Nb6 21. b3 { Now the Queenside is completely blocked and our attack on the Kingside can begin. } 21... Nc8 22. Bd2 Na7 23. Bc4 $18 Nc8 24. Rf1 $3 ( 24. h4 h5 25. g3 ( 25. g4 ) 25... Nb6 26. Bb5 ) 24... Qc7 25. Qe1 $3 Ra8 26. f4 Qa7 ( 26... Nb6 27. Bxa5 ) 27. Kh1 Nb6 28. Bb5 $18 ) 12... Ne8 13. Qc1 { Slightly unusual but absolutely playable. } 13... Bg4 14. Be2 Rb8 15. Bh6 Bxh6 16. Qxh6 Bxf3 { We are threatening Ng5 so Black needs to capture. } 17. Bxf3 { In the Benoni this exchange would give a good position but this is a Benko and it is easy for White to block the Queenside. } 17... Nc7 ( 17... Nc4 18. Be2 $1 Nxb2 19. Nb5 { The knight is almost trapped. } 19... c4 20. Ra3 $16 { [%csl Ga3][%cal Ya3h3] } ) 18. Be2 $1 Nd7 19. Nb5 Nf6 20. Qe3 Nxb5 21. Bxb5 Ne8 { Black wants to attack the bishop by ...Nc7. } 22. b3 Nc7 23. Bc4 { White has stabilized the Queenside and is much better. } 23... Rb4 { Putting a knight on b4 would be just horrible for Black! } ( 23... Qc8 24. Rad1 Na6 $2 { The knight will be in fact out of play on b4! For example } 25. f4 ( { or } 25. Rfe1 Nb4 26. Rd2 Qc7 27. h4 ( 27. f4 $5 ) 27... h5 28. Qh6 $18 ) 25... Nb4 26. Rd2 $18 ( 26. f5 $18 ) ) 24. f4 $16 Ne8 25. Rf3 ( 25. e5 ) 25... Kh8 26. Qc3+ f6 27. Re1 Ng7 28. Rh3 Qd7 29. Qg3 Rf7 1-0[Event "Krakow festival 7th"]

