1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. b6 Qxb6 6. Nc3 g6 7. a4 a5 { This is helping White as he now can put his bishop directly on b5. } 8. e4 d6 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Nf3 Bg7 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Nc4 Qc7 13. O-O { White has got a great position out of the opening. } 13... Bc8 14. f4 { This move and all the following alternatives are good for White! } ( 14. Bg5 $16 ) ( 14. h3 $16 ) ( 14. Re1 $16 ) 14... Nfd7 15. Bd2 $5 { Targeting the pawn on a5 and also stabilizing the position. What should Black play? He should not enter this position in the first place! } ( 15. f5 { is also often a good move. } 15... Ne5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Bh6 Rd8 18. Qf3 $16 ( { If White wants to be fancy he can try the rook lift } 18. Ra3 $16 { [%cal Ya3h3] } ) ) 15... Nb6 16. Qe2 Nxc4 17. Bxc4 Nd7 18. Rae1 $16 Nb6 19. Nb5 Qb7 20. b3 { Once again White succeeded in locking the Queenside - now he has a free hand on the Kingside. } 20... Bd7 21. Rb1 { White defends against ...Nxc4 followed by ...Bxb5. } ( 21. f5 { was also possible, e.g. } 21... Nxc4 22. bxc4 Bxb5 23. cxb5 Bd4+ ( 23... Qc7 24. Qc4 { Preventing ...c4 - Black is left without any counterplay. Soon White will start pushing pawns on the Kingside and win the game. } ) 24. Kh1 $16 ) 21... Nc8 22. Na3 Nb6 23. Qe1 Qa7 24. Kh1 Nc8 25. Bd3 Nb6 26. Nb5 Bxb5 27. Bxb5 Qc7 28. Bxa5 Rfb8 29. Bd2 c4 30. Bc6 Ra7 31. a5 Nc8 32. bxc4 e6 33. Qe3 Ne7 34. Rxb8+ Qxb8 35. Qb6 Nxc6 36. dxc6 1-0[Event "Ostend op"]
