{ A perfect game by the great Jeroen Piket! With the typical strategy of blocking the Queenside! } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. b6 d6 6. Nc3 Nbd7 7. e4 g6 8. a4 a5 9. Bb5 Bg7 10. Nf3 O-O 11. O-O Bb7 ( 11... Ba6 12. b7 $5 ( 12. Re1 Bxb5 13. axb5 $16 ) ) 12. h3 Nxb6 13. Bf4 Qc8 14. Re1 Rd8 15. Qc1 Ba6 16. Bh6 Bxb5 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nxb5 { Both moves are possible - taking with the pawn and taking with the knight. The idea in both cases is to block the Queenside. } 18... Rd7 19. Qc3 Kg8 20. b3 Qf8 21. Nd2 Qg7 22. Nc4 Nxc4 23. bxc4 { The Queenside is now totally blocked and White is strategically winning. } 23... Ne8 24. Rab1 { I wouldn't allow the exchange of queens - Black's queen could become a target once we attack on the Kingside. However White assessed the endgame as very favorable for him and he proved to be right. } 24... e6 25. e5 exd5 26. cxd5 $16 Nc7 $2 27. Nxc7 ( { White missed a nice continuation: } 27. Nxd6 $1 Rxd6 28. exd6 Qxc3 29. dxc7 $18 { and although White has only a rook for the queen his passers will decide the game. } ) 27... Rxc7 28. f4 Rd7 29. Qc4 Rad8 30. Rbd1 h6 31. Kh1 Qf8 32. Re3 Rb7 33. e6 fxe6 34. Rxe6 Qf7 35. Rde1 Qf5 36. Qc3 Rb1 37. Qxa5 Rdb8 38. Qc7 Rxe1+ 39. Rxe1 Rb1 40. Rxb1 Qxb1+ 41. Kh2 Qf5 42. Qxd6 c4 43. Qd8+ 1-0[Event "Gawlikowski mem 18th"]
