{ A very good game demonstrating the strategy with a white pawn on a5 (opposed to a black pawn) . White, even allowed the black knight to go to d4 but still he was much better - just as in the previous game! } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 { SUPER SOS! You will see 4.Nf3 in several games. The idea is to play b6 after 4...g6 5.cxb5 a6 6.b6!, avoiding the line 4.cxb5 a6 5.b6 e6! I do not suggest this line because Black has a very interesting alternative after 4.Nf3 - the move 4...b4! } 4... g6 $6 ( 4... b4 $1 ) 5. cxb5 a6 6. b6 $1 d6 7. Nc3 Nbd7 8. e4 Bg7 9. a4 Qxb6 10. a5 ( 10. Nd2 ) 10... Qb4 { With this Black is encouraging the move Ra4 because if White plays this then later the knight cannot go to a4. } 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Be2 Ne8 13. O-O Nc7 ( { Taking the pawn is out of the question as White would get a very strong attack, for instance } 13... Bxc3 14. bxc3 Qxc3 15. Ra3 Qg7 16. Nc4 $16 { [%cal Yc1b2] } ) 14. Nc4 Qb7 15. Na4 Nb5 16. Nab6 Nxb6 17. Nxb6 { Usually we take with the knight but axb6 is also possible. } 17... Ra7 18. Rb1 ( 18. Nxc8 $2 Rxc8 $13 { [%csl Gb5,Gg7] should of course not be played. We have lost several moves with our knight to exchange it against an undeveloped piece. } ) 18... Bd7 19. Bg5 $16 Re8 20. Qd2 Nd4 21. Bc4 Bb5 22. Qd3 ( 22. b3 $16 ) 22... Bxc4 23. Qxc4 Nb5 24. Qd3 Qb8 25. f4 { After having prevented any counterplay on the Queenside White starts to attack on the Kingside. } 25... Rc7 26. f5 Nd4 27. Rbc1 Be5 28. Bf4 Bxf4 29. Rxf4 Rf8 30. fxg6 fxg6 31. Rxf8+ Qxf8 32. Rf1 Qb8 33. h4 Nb5 34. h5 Qe8 35. e5 dxe5 36. Qg3 Nd6 37. Qxe5 gxh5 38. Rf3 h4 39. Qg5+ Kh8 40. Qh6 Nf7 41. Qh5 Kg8 42. Qxh4 Rb7 43. Qg4+ Kh8 44. Qh5 e5 45. d6 e4 46. Rf1 1-0[Event "Dos Hermanas op 5th"]
