{ Another very convincing win demonstration the strategy with a white pawn on a5! } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. Nf3 g6 5. cxb5 a6 6. b6 d6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. e4 O-O 9. a4 Qxb6 10. Nd2 Nbd7 11. a5 Qc7 12. Be2 Rb8 13. O-O Ne8 14. Nc4 Ne5 15. Nb6 f5 { This is Black's main source of counterplay. } ( 15... Nd7 16. Nca4 Nxb6 17. Nxb6 ( 17. axb6 ) ) 16. exf5 $1 ( 16. Ra3 $6 { is not good as Black is threatening } 16... f4 $13 { We should never allow that! } ) ( 16. Nxc8 $1 Qxc8 17. exf5 gxf5 ( { or } 17... Rxf5 18. Na4 $16 ) 18. Na4 $16 ) 16... Bxf5 17. Be3 { Insteat of taking on a6 (this pawn remains weak) White prefers to stabilize the position. } ( 17. Bxa6 $2 Qa7 18. Qe2 ( 18. Be2 $2 Rxb6 $17 ) 18... Nc7 $13 { gives Black counterplay. } ) 17... c4 $2 ( 17... Nd7 18. g4 { wins a piece. } ) 18. Ra4 $18 { White wins the pawn on c4 while a6 remains also weak. } 18... Nf6 19. Bxc4 Nfd7 20. Bxa6 Nc5 21. Nb5 Qd8 22. Bxc5 dxc5 23. Na3 Qc7 24. Bc4 Kh8 25. Nb5 Qd8 26. d6 Nxc4 27. Rxc4 exd6 28. Nxd6 Bd4 29. Nxf5 Rxf5 30. Rc2 Qd6 31. Re2 Rbf8 32. Qe1 Qf4 33. Re8 Bxb2 34. Rxf8+ Rxf8 35. a6 Qf6 36. Nd7 1-0[Event "World op 34th"]
