1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 { In this part of 4.e3 Nimzo for White, we focus on the lines, where Black plays the move ...d5. } 4... O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. a3 $5 { This is the first main position that we want to achieve. The idea is to grab the bishop pair at the cost of doubling the pawns, but then undouble the pawns on the next moves and try to make use of the long-term bishop pair advantage. } 6... Bxc3+ { Bishop retreats are connected with some concessions. } 7. bxc3 dxc4 $1 { This is how Black should proceed. The structure resulting from cxd5 exd5 is favourable for White! } ( 7... c5 $6 8. cxd5 $1 exd5 9. Ne2 { This and other continuations without taking on c4 lead to a great game for White, the main line being } 9... b6 10. O-O Ba6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Qd3 Nc7 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. c4 $14 { , where White successfully opens up the game for his bishop. } ) 8. Bxc4 c5 9. Ne2 Qc7 { Minor developing schemes with 9...b6 or 9... Nbd7 do not put pressure on White and is not satisfactory for Black. } 10. Bd3 Nc6 ( 10... e5 11. dxe5 Qxe5 12. O-O $14 { Our plan is Qc2, Bb2, and c3-c4, which is hard to stop. We kick the queen out of e5 with a tempo and get a nice pressure against Black's Kingside with our bishops. } ) 11. f4 $5 { We reach the main tabiya. We stop the ..e5 advance by force and our plan is to complete a very promising setup with 0-0, Ng3, Qe2, Bb2, possibly Rac1 or Rad1, and then go on to push e4 or f5, commencing a strong attack. As we will see in the games section, many Black players, even at a very high level, struggle to find sufficient counterplay with Black. } 11... b6 12. O-O Bb7 ( { Black's best counter-plan is connected with a quick fight for the e4 square: } 12... Ne7 $1 13. Ng3 Bb7 14. c4 cxd4 15. exd4 Nf5 $1 16. Nxf5 exf5 17. Bb2 Be4 $1 { Black achieves equality, as he is objectively able to in all serious openings. But the path requires concrete knowledge of a non-obvious idea. } 18. d5 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Ne4 20. Be5 Qe7 21. a4 $13 ) 13. Ng3 Rac8 ( 13... Ne7 $1 { transposes to 12...Ne7! } ) 14. Qe2 Rfd8 15. Bb2 $14 { Black has commonly struggled in positions like this, and for a good reason, because White is already better, as we will see in the games section. } *[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2024.02.16"]
[Round "?"]
[White "NIMZO 4.e3   FOR WHITE"]
[Black "FULL THEORY lines with d5"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[ECO "E49"]
[EventDate "2024.01.27"]
[PlyCount "37"]
[SourceVersionDate "2024.02.19"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. a3 $5 { This is a very interesting variation for White! We get it by force, it contains many positional and tactical traps and it is easy to learn!! } 6... Bxc3+ ( 6... Bd6 $6 7. c5 Be7 8. Nf3 { We get a space advantage, which gives us great long-term chances. If Black tries to undermine our Queenside, we are in time to stabilize the position: } 8... b6 9. b4 $16 a5 10. Bb2 ) ( 6... Be7 { This is illogical... now we can develop the knight on f3 from where it controls the center even better. } 7. Nf3 $14 b6 8. cxd5 exd5 9. b4 Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 11. Bb2 $14 { Black is quite passive. White has a clear plan to increase his advantage: } 11... Re8 12. b5 $1 Bd6 13. a4 Qe7 ( 13... Nf8 14. Ba3 $16 ) 14. Qb3 Nf8 15. Ba3 $16 { This is the typical strategy... to exchange the dark square bishops from a3!! } ) ( 6... dxc4 $5 7. Bxc4 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 c5 9. Ne2 { transposes to the main line } ) 7. bxc3 dxc4 $1 ( 7... c5 $6 { This is an inaccurate move which many people... with a low or a high rating, will play!! BE PREPARED AND GET A BIG ADVANTAGE WITH THE TYPICAL STRATEGIES! } 8. cxd5 $1 { Black has allowed this change of structure, which he shouldn't combine with giving up the bishop on c3! } 8... exd5 ( 8... Qxd5 9. Nf3 cxd4 10. cxd4 ( 10. exd4 $5 b6 11. c4 $1 Qd6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Bb2 Nbd7 14. Re1 $16 ( 14. h3 $14 ) ) 10... b6 11. Qe2 $14 ) 9. Ne2 b6 ( 9... Nc6 $6 10. O-O Re8 11. f3 b6 12. Ng3 Bb7 13. Ra2 $16 { A typical idea that makes the game very tough for Black. The rook will join the Kingside or the centre to support White's pawn advance. } ) 10. O-O Ba6 11. Bxa6 $1 Nxa6 12. Qd3 Nc7 ( 12... c4 $2 { Releasing the tension is a strategical mistake. } 13. Qc2 Re8 14. f3 Nc7 15. Ng3 $16 h5 ( 15... Qd7 $2 16. e4 $18 ) 16. Re1 $16 h4 17. Nf5 h3 18. e4 $16 ) ( 12... Qc8 13. Ng3 Re8 14. f3 Qb7 15. Re1 Rad8 16. Bb2 $14 { White is ready to push e3-e4 and it's not easy for Black to react, e.g. } 16... Nc7 17. e4 dxe4 18. fxe4 cxd4 19. cxd4 Qa6 ( 19... Ne6 20. d5 $18 ) 20. Qf3 $18 ) 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. c4 $14 { White opens up the game for his bishop and gets slightly better chances. Black's passed c-pawn is more of a weakness than a strength. } 14... dxc4 15. Qxc4 Qd5 16. Qc2 Rfd8 17. Ng3 Ne6 18. Bb2 $16 ) ( 7... b6 $6 { Innacurate for the same reason. } 8. cxd5 $1 exd5 9. Ne2 Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. Qd3 Qc8 12. O-O c5 13. Ng3 $14 Re8 14. f3 ) ( 7... Nbd7 $2 { Innacurate for the same reason. } 8. cxd5 $1 exd5 9. Ne2 $16 Re8 10. O-O b6 11. Ng3 ( 11. c4 $16 ) 11... Bb7 12. f3 c5 13. Ra2 $16 { see the game session! } ) 8. Bxc4 c5 $1 ( 8... b6 $6 { Very passive! } 9. Qf3 $3 { Disrupting Black's development. } ( { We could also play in the standard way with } 9. Ne2 { Black cannot just play "normal" moves and get a good game, as the following line illustrates: } 9... Bb7 10. f3 Nbd7 11. e4 c5 12. O-O Rc8 13. Bd3 Qe7 14. Bg5 $16 ) 9... c6 10. Ne2 Bb7 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Ng3 Qc7 13. e4 c5 14. Bb3 $16 ) ( 8... Nbd7 { We don't really need theory against non-critical moves like this one. } 9. Ne2 e5 ( 9... b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. f3 e5 12. e4 $16 ) 10. O-O b6 11. Ng3 Bb7 12. f3 $16 { Such positions are pure joy for White. } ( 12. a4 $16 { , intending to put the bishop on a3 is another plan. } ) ) 9. Ne2 ( 9. Bd3 Qc7 ) 9... Qc7 { Threatening ... cxd4 } ( 9... b6 $6 { Random fianchettoin' does not solve Black's problems and doesn't require much knowledge from White to play well against. } 10. O-O Bb7 ( 10... Ba6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Ng3 { We are ready to build a strong pawn centre. } 12... Nb8 13. Bb2 Nc6 ( 13... Nbd7 14. e4 $14 ) 14. Qe2 $14 ) 11. f3 $14 { We plan the typical e3-e4 advance. Black struggles to create counterplay. } 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Ba6 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. e4 Rc8 15. Be3 Nc7 16. Qb3 $16 { In positions like this, we have a clear advantage. We have a strong centre, a bishop, and prospects of Queenside pressure. Black's Queenside pawn majority is more of a weakness than a strength. } ) 10. Bd3 { Again Black has several possibilities, but only one move is satisfactory for him. In most other cases than 10...Nc6, White can immediately build a strong centre. } 10... Nc6 ( 10... e5 $6 { A good idea in a premature version. } 11. dxe5 $1 { Now black will have a misplaced queen on e5. White will stabilize and attack the queen with tempo! } 11... Qxe5 12. O-O { Generally the plan is Qc2-Bb2 and c3-c4. } 12... Nc6 ( 12... Bf5 $5 13. f4 $1 { This move is obviously strategically very risky, but it has a clear, concrete follow-up. } ( 13. Bxf5 $1 Qxf5 14. f3 $1 { This is also slightly better for White. } ( 14. c4 $5 Nc6 15. Ng3 Qe6 16. Bb2 Rad8 17. Qf3 $5 ) 14... Nc6 15. e4 Qe6 16. Bg5 Rfd8 17. Qc2 $14 ) 13... Qd5 14. Bxf5 Qxf5 15. Ng3 Qe6 ( 15... Qc8 16. e4 $16 ) ( 15... Qd5 16. e4 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 $16 ) 16. Qf3 Nc6 17. e4 $14 { We are better after we managed to push e3-e4. } ) ( 12... Rd8 $4 13. Bxh7+ ) 13. Qc2 $14 Rd8 ( 13... Qe7 14. c4 $14 ( 14. Ng3 $14 { is an alternative. Again, "normal-looking" moves don't work so well for Black: } 14... Be6 15. c4 Rad8 16. Bb2 $16 ) 14... Ne5 15. Bb2 { We don't even mind the exchange on d3. We get an initiative with opposite-coloured bishops, e.g. } 15... Nxd3 16. Qxd3 Be6 17. Nf4 Rad8 18. Qc2 Rfe8 19. e4 $14 ) ( 13... Be6 14. c4 $3 { A great possibility to carry out c3-c4 despite the hanging rook on a1. } 14... Qxa1 15. Bb2 Nb4 ( 15... Qxf1+ 16. Kxf1 $18 ) 16. axb4 Qa6 17. bxc5 $16 { White has tremendous compensation for the exchange. } ( 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. b5 Qd6 19. Bxh7+ Kh8 20. Nf4 $36 ) ) ( 13... Ng4 14. Ng3 ) 14. Bb2 $1 Qe7 15. c4 $14 Ne5 ( 15... Be6 16. Rad1 $16 ( 16. Nf4 $16 ) ( 16. h3 $16 ) ) 16. Rad1 ( 16. Bxe5 $14 Qxe5 17. Rae1 $1 { Slowly preparing e3-e4. } ( 17. Nc3 $2 Ng4 18. g3 Qh5 $36 ) 17... Bd7 18. Nc3 Bc6 19. h3 Qe7 20. e4 $14 ) 16... Nxd3 17. Rxd3 Be6 18. Nf4 $14 ) ( 10... b6 $6 11. e4 $1 Bb7 12. Bf4 Qc8 13. f3 Ba6 14. O-O Bxd3 15. Qxd3 Nbd7 16. a4 $16 { Stopping the pawn majority and preparing a4-a5 at some point. } ) ( 10... Nbd7 $6 11. e4 $1 e5 12. d5 Ne8 { This typical blockading maneuver is too passive in this case. } 13. c4 Nd6 14. O-O b6 15. Bb2 Ba6 16. Rc1 $16 { Black cannot increase pressure against c4, so he soon runs out of ideas, e.g. } 16... Rfe8 17. Ng3 Rac8 18. a4 $16 { After controlling everything on the Queenside, we are ready to prepare a breakthrough on the Kingside. } ) 11. f4 $5 { Our plan is to prevent ...e5 and then castle and continue with Ng3! and then Qe2 or Bb2... then Rac1 or Rad1... and at the right moment we either go for e3-e4! or for f4-f5! With perfect play the position is about equal... but, as many GM games have shown, the black position is a lot more difficult to handle! ....Black has the bad luck that natural-looking moves like ...Rac8-Rfd8 etc. etc. ARE INSUFFICIENT for equality!! } ( 11. e4 $2 { is a tactical mistake: } 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qc3+ $19 ) 11... b6 ( 11... cxd4 $6 12. cxd4 b6 13. O-O Bb7 14. Ng3 $36 { We continue with the Bb2, Qe2 setup. } 14... Rac8 15. Bb2 Rfd8 16. Qe2 $16 { We are ready to strike with f5 or e4. } ) ( 11... Ne7 $1 { is probably the best. } 12. O-O Bd7 13. e4 $14 Bc6 ( 13... Rfd8 14. Bb2 $14 ) 14. Ng3 { 14.e5 might be premature. } 14... Rad8 15. Be3 $14 { We will soon consider the f4-f5 push. } ) 12. O-O Bb7 ( 12... Rd8 $6 13. Ng3 $1 ( 13. Bb2 $6 { It is inaccurate to start with this, because of a quick attack against e3 followed by ...f5! } 13... Ng4 14. Rf3 c4 $3 ( 14... f5 $2 15. c4 $16 ) 15. Bc2 f5 $13 { Black has blocked the light squares and the position is no longer so attractive for White. } ) 13... Bb7 ( 13... Nd5 14. c4 $1 Nde7 15. Bb2 $16 ) 14. Qe2 $16 { White plans to build up his position with Bb2 and e4 at the right moment. Black has no good remedy against it. } ) 13. Ng3 $1 { Again, we start with this move and not Bb2. } 13... Rac8 ( 13... Rfd8 14. Qe2 $16 { transposes to 12...Rd8 } ) 14. Qe2 Rfd8 ( 14... Na5 15. Bb2 $14 { We plan to push e4 and Black has no easy counterplay, e.g. } ( { We have to watch out for ...Nb3: } 15. e4 $2 cxd4 16. cxd4 Nb3 ) 15... c4 $2 { A strategical mistake, because it releases the tension in the centre. } ( 15... Rfd8 { transposes to the main line } ) 16. Bc2 Nb3 17. Rae1 b5 18. e4 a5 19. e5 Nd5 20. f5 $18 { White's attack is very effective. Black's attempt at counterplay on the Queenside is not. } ) 15. Bb2 $14 Na5 { We can continue improving the position with Rac1 or Rad1. } 16. Rad1 $14 { Jumping to c4 doesn't solve Black's problems: } ( 16. Rac1 $14 ) 16... cxd4 17. cxd4 Nc4 18. Rc1 $1 b5 19. f5 $16 { We push at the right moment. The opening has been a success for White. } *[Event "ARG-ch 84th"]

