{The plan connected with ...Ne7 is Black's best idea (after avoiding all the traps in the various move orders)} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Bd3 Nc6 6. Nge2 d5 7. O-O dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O 9. a3 Bxc3 10. bxc3 Qc7 11. f4 Ne7 12. Bd3 b6 {Black prepares ...Bb7 and ...Nf5 ideas, fighting for the control of the e4-square will all of his minor pieces.} 13. Ng3 Bb7 (13... cxd4 {This also equalizes, but requires some non-standard choices from Black:} 14. cxd4 Nf5 15. Qe2 Qd7 $1 {A great move keeping Black fortified on the light squares. We will only face such play with very strong or well-prepared opponents.} (15... Nxg3 16. hxg3 Bb7 17. e4 {It's already not trivial for Black to react to White's attacking attempts.} h5 $1 {Securing the g4-square is the way to go.} (17... Rfd8 18. Bb2 $16) 18. Bb2 Ng4 19. e5 Bd5 20. f5 $14 {We still challenge Black to defend accurately.}) 16. Bb2 Bb7 17. Nh5 Nxh5 18. Qxh5 $13) 14. c4 cxd4 15. exd4 Nf5 (15... Rfd8 $6 {As in the main theory part, a "natural" move like this is already a bit dubious.} 16. Bb2 Rac8 17. a4 Ng6 18. Nh5 Nxh5 19. Qxh5 $14) 16. Nxf5 exf5 17. Bb2 Be4 {Black reaches his newly created e4-outpost. Black has played the opening very well and he gets equality, but it has to be said that these were all top engine moves that not many players know or are able to find over the board.} 18. d5 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Ne4 20. Be5 Qd7 21. a4 $13 f6 22. Bd4 {With a double-edged, objectively equal game.} 1/2-1/2

