{A great game that shows White's attacking potential in this line, even though White played some inaccuracies in the opening phase.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 c5 9. Ne2 Qc7 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. f4 b6 12. O-O Rd8 13. Bb2 $6 {For some reason this inaccuracy has been seen many times in high-level games.} (13. Ng3 $1) 13... Bb7 $6 {And it goes unpunished again.} (13... Ng4 $3 14. Rf3 c4 $3 15. Bc2 f5 $13) 14. e4 $2 {This adavnce is a bit too hasty here.} ({White should carry on with our main plan with} 14. Ng3) 14... Na5 $2 {Black removes the knight from the centre, allowing White to play Ng3.} (14... b5 $36) ({or} 14... Rac8 $15 {were moves that would make it hard for White to proceed without the Ng3 option.}) 15. Ng3 $14 Rac8 $6 (15... cxd4 16. cxd4 Nc4 17. Bxc4 Qxc4 18. Re1 $14) 16. e5 $3 Nd5 17. f5 $16 Ne3 18. Qh5 {White has a tremendous initiative for the exchange and he is winning!} exf5 (18... Nxf1 {White can win in a spectacular or prosaic fashion.} 19. Rxf1 $18 (19. f6 $18 gxf6 20. Qxh7+ Kf8 21. exf6 Ke8 22. Bb5+ Bc6 23. d5 $3 Bxb5 24. Qg8+ Kd7 25. Qxf7+ Kd6 26. Qxe6#) 19... g6 (19... Qc6 20. Rf2) 20. fxg6 fxg6 21. Bxg6 hxg6 22. Qxg6+ Qg7 23. Qxe6+ Kh8 24. Rf7 $18) 19. Nxf5 Nxf5 20. Rxf5 g6 21. Qg5 cxd4 22. cxd4 Nc4 23. Rc1 Bd5 24. Bxc4 $2 {White begins an inspired combination, but Black has ways to defend.} ({With} 24. Rf6 $18 {White could have won by gradually applying the pressure.}) 24... Bxc4 25. e6 fxe6 26. d5 exf5 $2 (26... exd5 $1 {allowed Black to hold, the point being} 27. Qf6 $6 (27. Be5 Qc5+ 28. Kh1 Rf8 29. Rf6 Rc6 $14 {Black defends against infiltration.}) 27... d4 $1) 27. Qf6 Rxd5 28. Re1 {The point. White wins convincingly.} Be2 29. Qh8+ Kf7 30. Qg7+ Ke6 31. Rxe2+ Kd6 32. Be5+ Rxe5 33. Qxe5+ Kc6 34. Rc2+ Kb7 35. Qd5+ Kb8 36. Rxc7 Rxc7 37. Kf2 a6 38. Kf3 Ka7 39. Kf4 Re7 40. Qd6 Rb7 41. Ke5 a5 42. Kd5 b5 43. Qd8 1-0

