{A high-level rapid game. It illustrates how to apply pressure against the 10...b6?! move. It also shows that Black remains solid despite being slightly worse in this line.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 c5 5. Bd3 d5 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O 9. Ne2 Qc7 10. Bd3 b6 $6 11. e4 $14 cxd4 (11... Bb7 12. Bf4 (12. f3) 12... Qc8 13. f3 $14) 12. cxd4 Ba6 13. O-O Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Nbd7 15. Bg5 ({The bishop would be a little better placed on f4:} 15. Bf4 $5 Qb7 16. f3 Rfd8 17. a4 $14 {Softening Black's Queenside:} a6 (17... Rac8 18. a5 $16) 18. Rab1 $14) 15... Qb7 16. f3 Rac8 17. a4 h6 18. Bh4 Rc6 19. Rfb1 Rfc8 20. a5 $14 {White has achieved a clear pressure. But Black goes on to defend well.} Rc4 21. axb6 axb6 22. Ra2 Qc6 23. Rab2 Rc2 24. h3 Qa4 25. Rxc2 Qxc2 26. Qxc2 Rxc2 27. Kf1 Ne8 28. Be7 (28. Ra1 $14 {kept White at least slightly better. The rook is more effective attacking Black's camp from behind.}) 28... f5 $1 {A great equalizing breakthrough!} 29. exf5 exf5 30. d5 Rd2 31. Nf4 g5 32. Bb4 Rd4 33. Ng6 Kf7 34. Nh8+ Kg8 35. Ng6 Kf7 36. Bc3 Rxd5 37. Nh8+ Kg8 38. Ng6 Kf7 39. Nh8+ Kg8 40. Ng6 Kf7 1/2-1/2

