1. d4 e6 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 { This is a different line against the Nimzo and we don't have a clear transposition. Still, the plans are similar and the game is quite exemplary. } 4... d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 O-O 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 b6 9. Bd3 Ba6 10. Ne2 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Re8 12. O-O c5 13. Ng3 Nc6 14. Bb2 Qd7 $6 ( { The best move, recommended by current theory, is } 14... h5 $1 { It's not so trivial for White to push e3-e4 through then, e.g. } 15. Rae1 h4 16. Nf5 h3 $13 { White can play e4, but he has made the concession of allowing the pawn to h3 and Black can generate counterplay. } ) 15. e4 $1 { White achieves his ideal breakthrough. } 15... dxe4 $2 { Black shouldn't open the f-file for the rook because of the Rxf6 ideas. But his position would be much worse anyway. } 16. fxe4 { It's already hard to suggest a defence. } 16... Ne5 ( 16... Rad8 { runs straight into } 17. Rxf6 $1 gxf6 18. Nh5 $18 ) ( 16... Qg4 { was the most stubborn, but probably also lost after the simple } 17. Rae1 $16 ) 17. Qe2 Ng6 18. Rxf6 $1 { Black's position gets shattered after this thematic exchange sacrifice. } 18... gxf6 19. Nh5 Re6 20. d5 Rd6 21. c4 Ne5 22. Qf2 Kf8 23. Qg3 Re8 24. Qg7+ Ke7 25. Rf1 1-0[Event "2010 Greek Team Youth Ch."]
