{An amazing performance by White!} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 (4. e3 $1 {This would be our move order} O-O 5. Bd3 d5 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 c5 $6 {Remember the rule: Black must not allow BOTH of these things to happen: 1) give up the pair of bishops; 2) allow the move cxd5! for White! In other words, Black must prevent one of these 2 things!} (7... dxc4 $1 {is the only good move!}) 8. cxd5 $1 {so we got to play cd5! ,,while having the pair of bishops.. .white is better!} exd5 9. Ne2 Nbd7 $6 (9... b6) (9... Nc6 $6) 10. O-O b6 11. f3 Bb7 12. Ra2 Re8 {etc. etc.}) 4... d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 O-O 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 Re8 9. Bd3 b6 10. Ne2 Bb7 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Ra2 Nf8 13. Ng3 $16 c5 14. Re2 cxd4 15. cxd4 Qd7 16. Bb2 {According to the computer, White is winning!!} Ne6 17. Qd2 $1 {xf4} Rad8 18. Nf5 Nf8 19. g4 $3 {the move 19.e4 would activate all of Black's forces! The great move 19.g4!! is keeping them all inactive!} h6 20. Rg2 N6h7 21. h4 Qa4 22. Bc2 Qd7 23. Re1 Rc8 24. Bb1 Ng6 25. e4 Qd8 (25... dxe4 {also fails clearly:} 26. fxe4 Nf6 27. d5 ({Not} 27. h5 $2 Nxe4 $1) 27... Ne5 28. Bxe5 Rxe5 29. g5 $18 (29. Qf4 $18)) 26. g5 hxg5 27. hxg5 Nhf8 28. e5 Ne6 29. Rg4 Rc6 30. Rf1 Nef8 31. f4 Bc8 32. Rg3 Bxf5 33. Bxf5 Nh4 34. Bd3 (34. Bg4 {was another way to get the job done:} Ree6 35. f5 $18 ({Of course not} 35. Bxe6 $4 fxe6 {and suddenly Black has a significant compensation for the exchange thanks to the light-squared blockade.})) 34... g6 35. Rh3 Nf5 36. Qh2 {A perfect game for the positions where black gave up the pair of bishops AND allowed the move cxd5.} 1-0

