{ In this part of the Nimzo 4.e3 repertoire we deal with the lines without ... d5 for Black, or with ...d5 combined with ...c5. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O ( 4... b6 { Against this move we choose } 5. Ne2 { intending to get the bishop pair without spoiling the structure with a3 next. Black's main move, } 5... c5 { preserves the bishop for the time being. We play } 6. a3 Ba5 7. Rb1 $1 { to force Black's knight to a less-than-ideal a6-square. } 7... Na6 { We proceed with } 8. Nf4 Bb7 9. Bd3 { finally forcing ...Bxc3+ here or on the next move. After } 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 O-O 11. O-O { We threaten f2-f3 and e3-e4. Black should better exchange the light-squared bishops, but it doesn't solve his opening problems as we still build up the centre: } 11... Be4 12. f3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 { e.g. } 13... Nc7 14. e4 d6 15. Ne2 $16 { Finally regrouping the knight to the more suitable g3-square with an excellent outcome of the opening. } ) ( 4... c5 5. Ne2 b6 { transposes to 4... b6 } ) ( 4... Bxc3+ $6 { Lesser lines like this one do not work very well for Black, but White should now have the correct setup. } 5. bxc3 O-O 6. Bd3 d6 7. Ne2 $1 { Very importantly, we put the knight on e2 and not on f3. The e3-e4 expansion is our main idea. A typical way the game could go on runs as follows: } 7... Re8 8. e4 e5 9. f3 Nbd7 10. Be3 c5 11. d5 Nf8 12. Qd2 Ng6 13. O-O $16 { With a position that is clearly better for White, but Black attempts to create a fortress that will be tough to break. We should improve and prepare the Kingside attack gradually, without rushing. } ( { or } 13. h4 $16 ) ) 5. Bd3 c5 6. Ne2 cxd4 7. exd4 d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. O-O Nc6 10. Nxd5 $1 { This is the main idea of this part of the repertoire. We strive for a position with symmetrical structure, but greater activity for White. The resulting positions are risk-free and offer a good enough practical pull. } 10... exd5 ( { Black gets punished for recapturing with the queen, e.g. } 10... Qxd5 $6 11. a3 Be7 12. Qc2 g6 13. Rd1 $16 { Black could stand very well if he was given several tempi to consolidate, but this is not the case. } ) 11. Nf4 $14 { Our main line runs } 11... Bd6 12. Re1 $1 Qf6 13. Nxd5 Qxd4 14. Be3 Qh4 15. g3 Qg4 16. Nf4 $14 { with an endgame that can be safely and successfully pressed for a win. Black plays only for a draw and doesn't even have full equality because of the better activity of White's pieces. } ( { or } 16. Bf1 $14 ) *[Event "MODERN CHESS"]

