1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 b6 { This line used to be popular in the past... but not so much anymore. } 5. Ne2 $1 { This is the most simple move. White connects the knights and then plays a3. } 5... c5 $5 ( 5... Bb7 $6 { This is not the idea!!! } 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Nxc3 O-O 8. Bd3 $16 Bxg2 $2 9. Rg1 Bb7 10. e4 $18 ) ( 5... Ba6 $5 6. a3 Bxc3+ ( 6... Be7 7. Nf4 $14 d5 8. cxd5 Bxf1 9. Kxf1 Nxd5 ( 9... exd5 10. g4 $16 ) 10. Ncxd5 exd5 11. Bd2 O-O 12. Rc1 c6 13. h4 $36 ( 13. g3 $14 ) ) 7. Nxc3 d5 8. b3 $14 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 ( 9... dxc4 10. bxc4 Nc6 11. a4 $14 ( 11. O-O Na5 12. Qa4 Qd7 13. Qb4 $14 ) ) 10. a4 Na5 11. Ba3 Re8 12. Rb1 $14 dxc4 $4 13. b4 $18 Qe7 14. Qc1 Nb3 15. Rxb3 cxb3 16. Bxa6 ) 6. a3 Ba5 7. Rb1 $1 { Forcing the awkward ...Na6 } 7... Na6 8. Nf4 ( 8. g3 $5 Bb7 9. d5 { this is the most common line, but I prefer 8.Nf4 } ) 8... Bb7 9. Bd3 Bxc3+ { Black does not have much choice other than to take on c3 here or on the next move, as otherwise, the knight is ready to go, leaving the bishop in trouble on a5. } 10. bxc3 O-O 11. O-O $14 { Black has a bad version of the doubled pawns position. If he doesn't do something, his bishop will be closed with f2-f3 and his knight will remain misplaced on a6. } 11... Be4 { This is Black's most sensible try, exchanging the bishops before White plays f3. } ( 11... d5 $2 12. cxd5 exd5 13. f3 $16 { We know from part 1 of the course that similar positions are quite bad for Black. } ( { or } 13. Ne2 $16 { with a typical regroupment, e.g. } 13... Nc7 14. Ng3 Re8 15. f3 Ne6 16. Rb2 Rc8 17. Rbf2 ) ) ( 11... d6 $6 12. Ne2 $3 { The knight should move to the most desired g3-square. } 12... Nc7 13. Ng3 e5 14. d5 Re8 15. e4 $16 { With a typical big advantage. } ) 12. f3 $1 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 { We are ready to advance the centre with e4 and d5. } 13... Nc7 ( 13... d6 14. e4 Nb8 15. d5 e5 16. Ne2 $16 ) 14. e4 d6 15. Ne2 $16 *[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
