1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Ne2 cxd4 $5 ( 6... d5 $5 { In this move order, we get to choose into which line we will go!! We can choose the early ...d5 lines (after 7.a3!) or the regular ...c5-cxd4 lines (after 7.cd5!) . } 7. cxd5 $1 ( 7. a3 $1 { This is also good and it will transpose to the lines with the fast ...d7-d5 for Black! } 7... dxc4 ( 7... cxd4 $6 { This is known to be bad! } 8. axb4 dxc3 9. Nxc3 $3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 Nc6 12. b5 Nb4 13. Ke2 $16 ) 8. Bxc4 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 { We have a transposition to the part 1 of our repertoire. } ) 7... cxd4 $1 ( 7... exd5 $6 8. a3 $1 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 $14 ) 8. exd4 Qxd5 $5 { This is another interesting alternative! } ( 8... Nxd5 9. O-O { transposes to the main line } 9... Nf6 { This is playable... and again we get nice active play with the typical isolated pawn. } 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Bc2 $1 Nc6 12. a3 b6 13. Qd3 g6 14. Rad1 Bb7 15. Qh3 $14 ( 15. Bb3 $14 ) ) 9. O-O $5 Qh5 $5 ( 9... Qd7 $5 { This is playable too since there is no Nf3-e5 to be played. } 10. Bc2 $3 Nc6 ( 10... Bxc3 11. bxc3 Qc7 12. Bg5 Nbd7 13. Qd3 $16 ) ( 10... b6 $2 11. Bg5 $16 { With a very nice trick to follow!! } 11... Be7 $2 ( 11... Nd5 12. Qd3 g6 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Nf4 $16 ) 12. Bxf6 $3 Bxf6 13. Qd3 g6 14. Qf3 $18 { With a decisive double attack. } ) 11. Qd3 Be7 12. a3 ( 12. Be3 $4 Nb4 $17 ) 12... Rd8 13. Rd1 b6 14. Bg5 $16 { With a very good version of the typical isolated pawn!! } 14... g6 15. h4 ( 15. Ba4 $16 ) 15... Bb7 16. Rac1 $16 ) 10. Ne4 $1 ( 10. a3 $5 Bd6 11. Bf4 Bxf4 12. Nxf4 Qxd1 13. Rfxd1 $14 { Black is several tempi behind in his development, so he cannot stabilize and play against our isolated pawn in the endgame. } 13... Nc6 14. d5 $14 ) 10... Nbd7 ( 10... Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Nc6 12. Qd3 $14 { Black has some problems with his queen placement. } 12... Bd6 13. Nf4 Bxf4 14. Bxf4 $16 ) 11. a3 ( 11. Qc2 $14 ) 11... Be7 12. Qc2 $14 { It is not easy for Black to solve the issue of his passive bishop on c8. } ) 7. exd4 d5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 ( 8... Qxd5 $5 { AGAIN THIS WILL TRANSPOSE Check the comment on move 6...d5 instead of 6...cxd4 } ) ( 8... exd5 $6 9. Bg5 $14 { With a risk-free advantage as now our Ne2 is very well placed, much better than it would be on f3! } ) 9. O-O Nc6 10. Nxd5 $1 { We choose this nice move because our repertoire is based on simplicity. It is important to be the one who determines the pattern of play! } 10... exd5 ( 10... Qxd5 $6 { This is not so good! Black's dream of giving White an isolated pawn, developing, stabilizing the position, and pressing... is several tempi away from happening! Black is underdeveloped, his queen is vulnerable on d5 and White will develop his pieces with tempo... in other words: a risk-free advantage for White! } 11. a3 $1 { This is good, but White has at least 2 good alternatives: 11.Qc2 and 11.Be3. It is not a matter of concrete moves now, we just put our pieces in the center and prevent Black's plans!! } ( 11. Qc2 $1 h6 12. Rd1 Be7 13. a3 Qd8 14. Bh7+ $1 { It is always good to include this check!!! } 14... Kh8 15. Be4 Bd7 16. Bd2 $3 { Putting the bishop on c3 may be the most surgically precise continuation. } ( 16. d5 $1 exd5 17. Rxd5 $16 Qe8 18. Bd2 Be6 19. Rd3 $16 Rc8 20. Bc3 ) ( 16. Bf4 $5 Rc8 17. Qd3 $14 ) 16... Rc8 17. Bc3 Bf6 18. Qd3 $16 ) ( 11. Be3 $1 ) 11... Be7 12. Qc2 g6 13. Rd1 $16 { It will take too much time for Black to put his knight on d5!! } 13... Bf6 ( 13... Qa5 14. Be3 Bd7 15. Be4 Bf6 ( 15... Rac8 16. b4 Qd8 17. Qd2 $16 ) 16. Nc3 $16 ( 16. b4 Qd8 17. Qd2 $16 ) ) ( 13... Qd8 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Be4 Bd7 16. d5 { White will have a free initiative in a symmetrical structure after this break. } ( 16. Nc3 $16 ) 16... exd5 17. Bxd5 $16 { e.g. } 17... Bf6 18. Ng3 Rc8 19. Qb3 ) 14. Be4 Qd8 15. Bxc6 $16 bxc6 16. Bh6 $1 ( 16. Bf4 $1 { Preparing to put the bishop on e5 is also strong. } 16... Ba6 17. Ng3 Qb6 18. Be5 $16 ) 16... Bg7 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 { White has achieved a classical good minor piece vs. a bad minor piece. Taking the c6-pawn right away is not even necessary to preserve a big edge. } 18. Rac1 $16 ( 18. Qxc6 $16 Rb8 19. b4 Bb7 20. Qc3 ) ) 11. Nf4 $14 Bd6 ( 11... Nxd4 $2 12. Bxh7+ Kxh7 13. Qxd4 $16 ) ( 11... Be7 $6 { A bit passive } 12. Be3 Bf6 13. Rc1 $16 g6 14. Re1 $16 ( 14. Rc5 $16 Ne7 ( 14... Be6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Qg4 ) 15. Qf3 b6 16. Nxd5 $1 ( 16. Rc3 $16 { this is also simple and good } ) 16... Nxd5 17. Rxd5 Qe7 18. Qf4 Bb7 19. Rd6 $16 ) ) ( 11... g6 12. Bc2 $14 ( 12. Be3 Bd6 13. Bc2 $14 ) ) 12. Re1 $1 { it is very important to play this move here! ...Black is threatening to equalize with Bxf4! and Qf6!-Bf5! } ( 12. Be3 Bxf4 $1 13. Bxf4 Qf6 14. Be3 Bf5 $13 ) 12... Qf6 ( 12... Bxf4 13. Bxf4 Qf6 14. Be5 $14 { This is the difference with the Re1 move! } 14... Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Be6 16. Qd2 { With a very pleasant and risk-free advantage for White!! } 16... Rac8 17. Rae1 $14 ) ( 12... Ne7 $2 13. Qf3 $16 ( 13. h3 $16 { the idea is to remove the h2 pawn from all the Bxh2+ versions! } 13... Bf5 14. Nxd5 $1 Bh2+ 15. Kxh2 Qxd5 16. Bf1 $16 ( 16. Kg1 $16 Qxd4 17. Rxe7 Qxd3 18. Qxd3 Bxd3 19. Rxb7 $16 ) ) ) ( 12... Re8 13. Rxe8+ Qxe8 14. Be3 $14 Nb4 15. Bb1 Qb5 16. a3 Nc6 17. Qc2 g6 18. Qd2 $14 ) ( 12... Qh4 13. g3 Qg4 14. Nxd5 $14 ) 13. Nxd5 Qxd4 14. Be3 $14 { Once again with a very nice advantage without complications! } 14... Qh4 ( 14... Qg4 15. h3 Qxd1 16. Raxd1 $14 Be6 17. Be4 ) 15. g3 Qg4 16. Nf4 $14 ( 16. Bf1 $14 Qxd1 17. Raxd1 ) 16... Qxd1 17. Raxd1 { 1-0 Tregubov,P-Monroy,C/ Tallinn 2016/CBM 176 Extra/[,ĂéÜííçň] } *[Event "?"]

