{In this amazing game by the world champion, he shows many of the typical plans of the Nimzo with double c-pawns for White... He puts his knight on the ideal square e3 (which is almost impossible to achieve if Back plays well) and soon his opponent is left without any counterplay... study it carefully and learn a lot!!} 1. e3 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 b6 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. d4 Bb4 6. Bd3 {This is not our theory, but we get a similar position to the ones that can arise in our repertoire. Learning ideas occurring here will be beneficial.} Ne4 7. O-O Bxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Ne1 $1 {Immediately preparing f3 to kick the knight out of e4.} c5 10. f3 Nf6 11. e4 Ne8 ({The following line shows why attempting a central break is counterproductive for Black:} 11... d5 $2 12. cxd5 exd5 13. e5 Nfd7 14. f4 {When we play this typical advance, the main thing we need is a good response to ...f5, e.g.} f5 15. g4 $1 ({Not} 15. exf6 $2 Nxf6) 15... g6 16. Ng2 $18 {The knight will increase the pressure on the f5-pawn and there's no good way to hold Black's position together.}) 12. d5 d6 13. Nc2 Nd7 (13... exd5 $2 {Undoubling the pawns would only further worsen Black's position.} 14. cxd5 Nd7 15. c4 $18 {The game is strategically won for White.}) (13... e5 14. Ne3 Nd7 15. a4 {White stops all the potential pawn breaks to suffocate Black.} g6 16. Ra2 Ng7 17. g4 f6 18. Rg2 $16 {In a position like this, White is much better, but Black tries to establish a fortress. There's a tough game ahead trying to break Black's resistance.}) 14. Ne3 Nef6 15. a4 a5 16. Ra2 Qc7 17. f4 exd5 (17... e5 {is always met with} 18. f5 {White has a free roll on the Kingside with zero counterplay for Black. He must be winning, e.g.} h6 19. g4 Nh7 20. h4 f6 21. Rg2 $18) 18. exd5 Rfe8 19. g4 Nf8 (19... Ne4 20. Qf3 $1 {and the knight gets trapped:} Nxc3 21. Ra3 $18) 20. g5 {White builds up the attack while Black is reduced to passivity. Black's position is long beyond salvation.} N6d7 (20... Ne4 21. Qc2 $18) 21. h4 Rad8 22. h5 Bc8 (22... g6 23. Rh2 $18) 23. Ng4 Re7 24. Rg2 Kh8 25. Qf3 Rde8 26. Qg3 Rd8 (26... Nb8 27. f5 $18) (26... f5 27. gxf6 Nxf6 28. Nxf6 gxf6 29. Qg8#) 27. Bd2 Rde8 28. f5 Ne5 29. Nxe5 Rxe5 30. Bf4 Nd7 31. f6 g6 32. hxg6 fxg6 33. Bxg6 hxg6 34. f7 Rf8 35. Bxe5+ Nxe5 36. Qh4+ Kg7 37. Qh6# 1-0

