{ In this bonus part, I included three games that reached the thematic knight vs. bishop symmetrical endgame, that was famously won by Fischer against Saidy. Acquaintance with the plans of this endgame will be of great benefit to us if we happen to get it or consciously steer into it in a practical game resulting from the symmetrical structure of the main line. The endgame should objectively be held by the bishop's side. In practice, it is not such an easy task. } 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Ndb5 Bb4 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d5 9. e3 O-O 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Be2 Bf5 12. Nb5 Qb6 13. O-O a6 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Qxd4 16. exd4 Rac8 17. Bd1 Bc2 18. Be3 Bxd1 19. Rfxd1 Rc2 20. Rd2 Rfc8 21. Rxc2 Rxc2 22. Rc1 Rxc1+ 23. Bxc1 { 0-1 Saidy, A-Fischer, R USA-ch New York 1963 (11) } *[Event "USA-ch"]
[Event "New York"]
[Site "New York"]
