{ The Gruenfeld Defence is one of the most challenging responses to 1.d4. Beeing very well prepared, the Gruenfeld players are usually looking for dynamic play. Therefore, I have put a lot of time and effort to find a solid and reliable system that you can use in the long run. The starting position of our repertoire arises after } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Qb3 { A very interesting positional line for White. We get it completely by force and Black needs to know the only good move here. Even if Black knows the best lines, we get interesting strategic positions with various plans for both sides. In other words: A great practical choice! } *[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[Site "Germany"]
[Date "2024.01.28"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Grunfeld Qb3 lines"]
[Black "Theory and Plans"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[ECO "D95"]
[EventCountry "GER"]
[EventDate "2014.09.21"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventType "team-tourn"]
[PlyCount "25"]
[Source "ChessBase"]
[SourceDate "2015.06.18"]
[SourceQuality "1"]
[SourceVersion "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "2015.06.18"]

1. d4 { The best way to play against the Grunfeld is to choose different sidelines, as the main lines are often very drawish after 30+ moves of theory. We are doing something similar. } 1... Nf6 2. Nf3 { not our move order, make sure to follow the subvariation for exact move order. } ( 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 { The starting position of the Grunfeld. } 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. e3 O-O 6. Qb3 { this is, of course, the most common move order } ) 2... g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 d5 5. e3 { Appears to be very quiet but White has sneaky plans to open up the center in the middlegame. We aim to stabilize the position and develop the pieces first before central breaks. } 5... O-O ( 5... c5 $2 { Unlike other Grunfeld lines, this typical move does not work! White is much better here, in fact almost winning. And yet, many players will play it! } 6. dxc5 Qa5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 ( 7... Ne4 { doesn't make things any better. } 8. Bd2 Nxc3 9. Bxc3 $1 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qxc3+ 11. Nd2 $18 { Black can't even capture on c5 now. } ) 8. Qxd5 Bxc3+ 9. Bd2 { White is simply winning! } 9... Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qxc5 $4 { Huge blunder, make sure to know the upcoming trick. } 11. Rc1 Qf5 12. Nd4 Qd7 13. Bb5 $18 { With a cool victory. } ) 6. Qb3 { A very interesting positional line for White. We get it completely by force...and Black needs to know the only good move here. Even if black knows the best move, we get interesting strategic positions with various plans for both sides. In other words: A great practical choice ! } 6... e6 $1 { The only good move for Black. } ( 6... c6 { playable but a bit passive! } 7. a4 $1 { this is the move I prefer along with 7.h3! Planning a5-Be2 and short castle. } ( 7. h3 $1 { a usefull waiting move..stopping any Bg4 ideas ! } 7... b6 8. a4 { Planning a5 with similar ideas as in the mainline. } ) 7... a5 ( 7... e6 8. a5 $1 { White is better due to huge space advantage. } 8... Nbd7 9. Be2 { Black is too passive. } ) 8. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 ( 8... cxd5 9. Bd2 $14 { White has nice risk-free pressure on the queensdie because the g7 Bishop is misplaced. } ) 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Be2 Nc6 11. O-O { we plan to later use the b5-square and penetrate from the Queenside. } ) ( 6... dxc4 $6 { This is a common mistake but is seen from time to time. } 7. Bxc4 { We usually recapture with the Bishop, if we can get the Bishop developed in one go, ie we haven't committed Bd3 or Be2 yet. } 7... Nc6 $1 { The best option, intending Na5. } ( 7... c5 $1 8. d5 $14 { Once again we follow our predetermined plans. } 8... Nbd7 ( 8... Ne8 { planning Nd6. } 9. O-O Nd6 10. e4 $14 { Again, we don't mind giving the light-squared Bishops when he has achieved the central bind with e4 and d5 pawns. } 10... Bg4 11. Nd2 $16 ) ( 8... a6 $1 9. a4 { stopping b5. } 9... Ne8 10. O-O Nd6 11. a5 $14 { stopping b5 and creating a hole on b6 for our knight. } ) 9. O-O Nb6 10. e4 $16 { not caring about the light squared Bishop, we plan Be3, Rc1 & Rd1. } ) ( 7... a6 $2 { Typical and common mistake. } 8. O-O b5 $6 ( 8... c5 $2 9. dxc5 $16 { Black will now lose some time to regain the pawn, and until then we will complete our development. } ) ( 8... Nc6 { planning Na5. } 9. Be2 { The best way to prevent Na5. } 9... b5 ( 9... Be6 10. Qd1 $16 { We have lost some tempi but in return, Black's piece placement has been disturbed. He also cannot try his usual c5/e5 breaks. } ) 10. Rd1 Bb7 11. e4 $16 { As a principle, we should always play e4 when we are completely certain about the outcomes. } ) 9. Be2 { White is much better. } 9... Bb7 $6 10. a4 $16 { White huge positional advantage. Black has too many weaknesses. } ) ( 7... c6 8. a4 $1 { Just one thing to remmember, in case of ...c6, a4 is the best reply to stop b5. } 8... Nbd7 9. e4 { planning Be3, 0-0 with usual positional play. } 9... Nb6 10. Be2 $16 { It is very important to save this bishop in such positions. } ) ( 7... b6 { planning Bb7, but this also weakens light squares as you will see in the upcoming lines. } 8. O-O Bb7 ( 8... Ba6 { is a really bad move, Black can't afford to trade lightsquared Bishops. } 9. Rd1 { Keeping calm, trading light squared bishops is always in our favor. } ) 9. e4 $14 { One of the rare but important tactical theme! we are not hanging the e4-pawn. } 9... Nc6 ( 9... Nxe4 $4 { looses on the spot } 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Ng5 $18 ) 10. Qa4 { stepping away from Na5. } ) ( 7... Nfd7 $6 { planning c5. } 8. O-O c5 9. d5 { typical way to meet c5, when we are well developed. } 9... a6 10. a4 Nb6 11. e4 $16 { In situations with pawns on e4,d5 we allow Black to capture our light squared Bishop. } ) ( 7... Nbd7 $6 8. O-O $1 { with usual plans. We don't need to memorize anything here, just understand the plans. } ) 8. Be2 $1 { We don't want to move our queen to keep more flexibility. } 8... Nd7 $6 { Once again planning Nb6, a5-a4-a3 & e5. } ( 8... Na5 $2 { loses time } 9. Qc2 $16 ( 9. Qa4 $16 { is also possible. } ) 9... Bf5 10. e4 { Planning Be3 next, Black's knight on a5 is out of the game. } ) ( 8... b6 $2 { is usually not a good idea, Black weakens the light squares. } 9. O-O Bb7 10. Rd1 { Simple developement } 10... Na5 11. Qc2 Qc8 12. b4 $16 { All of this sounds so natural, White is further restricting Black's knight. } ) ( 8... e5 $2 { very provocative and doesn't work either. } 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. f4 Nc5 12. Qc2 $16 { We stabilize with a little bit of care. } ) ( 8... Qd6 { planning e5, but we always have d5 in our hands. } 9. O-O e5 10. d5 Ne7 11. e4 $16 { White has huge space advantage } ) 9. O-O Nb6 ( 9... e5 10. d5 { just our typical way to meet e5. } 10... Ne7 11. e4 $16 { Once again we establish this central bind. } ) 10. Rd1 a5 11. h3 $16 { stopping Bg4 thus planning e4. } ) ( 6... c5 $2 { Simply loses a pawn. } 7. cxd5 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nbd7 9. Bc4 Nb6 10. O-O $16 { This is too much too handle for Black. White will continue with e4. } ) 7. Be2 $1 { The most simple, from now on if Black takes on c4 we usually capture with the queen. } ( 7. cxd5 $2 { Don't decide too quick in chess, it's always good to keep tension. } 7... exd5 $36 { Black has a good version of QGD. } ) 7... b6 $1 { The best response. } ( 7... a6 { planning dxc4-b5. } 8. O-O dxc4 9. Qxc4 $1 b5 10. Qb3 Bb7 11. a4 { of course, we follow our typical plans. } ) ( 7... c6 8. O-O { Keeping the tension. } 8... Nbd7 9. a4 $14 { Gaining more space, White has the best version of semi slav. } ) ( 7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 $14 { We always recapture on c4 with the queen when we have commited Bd3 or Be2. } 8... b6 9. b4 $14 { The best move intending to meet Ba6 with b5. } 9... Ba6 10. b5 ) ( 7... c5 $6 { pretty dubious it makes sense to develop first. } 8. dxc5 Na6 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxa6 Nxc3 11. bxc3 bxa6 12. O-O $14 Qc7 13. Ba3 $16 { White has an amazing position, in fact Black is stuck. } ) 8. O-O { We first wait for Bb7. } 8... Bb7 ( 8... dxc4 9. Qxc4 $1 { Again, remember to recapture with your queen in such cases. } 9... Ba6 10. Qa4 Bxe2 11. Nxe2 Nbd7 12. b4 $14 { With no troubles whatsoever } ) 9. Rd1 { eyeing the d8 queen. } 9... Nbd7 10. cxd5 { Now that Black has commited Bb7, we want to capture on d5. } 10... exd5 11. a4 { The idea of a4 .. is to provoke a5 by black..and after that, the move c7-c5 would be less attractive due to the weakness of b5 ! } 11... a5 12. Ne5 $14 Re8 13. f4 $14 { White's main plan in such positions is Bd2-Be1-Bh4, he is better. } *[Event "?"]

