1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nf3 ( 4. Bg5 { is another playable move order. By keeping back Nf3 White can fight against Black's idea with ...g5 and ...Nh5. For example } 4... O-O ( { Black cannot immediately exchange the g5-bishop due to } 4... h6 5. Bh4 g5 6. Bg3 Nh5 7. Be5 $1 f6 $2 8. e3 $18 { [%csl Rh5][%cal Yd1h5] } ) 5. e3 ( 5. e4 $5 h6 ( 5... d6 6. Qd2 ) 6. Be3 ) 5... d6 ( 5... c5 6. d5 h6 7. Bh4 Qb6 8. Rb1 { --> see model game Filguira-Kourkoulos } ) 6. Be2 $5 { By reversing the move order (Be2 before Nf3) White keeps h5 under control, preventing ...g5 followed by ...Nh5. } ) 4... O-O ( 4... c5 { Another possible move order. } 5. d5 ( 5. e4 { With this, we get a Maroczy bind - also a good choice! } 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nc6 7. Be3 ) 5... O-O 6. Bg5 d6 7. e3 { and we have transposed to the main line. } ) 5. Bg5 d6 ( 5... c5 6. d5 b5 $2 { Black can try this kind of Benko gambit here and also within the next few moves. It doesn't work in the Smyslov System - we capture the pawn and keep it! } ( 6... d6 7. e3 { transposes } ) 7. cxb5 a6 8. e3 axb5 ( 8... Qa5 9. Nd2 $16 ) 9. Bxb5 Ba6 10. Bxa6 ( { or } 10. a4 Bxb5 11. axb5 $16 ) 10... Rxa6 11. O-O d6 12. e4 $16 ) 6. e3 { Now we have a simple plan of development: 1) If Black plays normal moves like ...d6, ...Nbd7, ...e5, ...c6, etc, our plan is Be2, 0-0, Qc2!, and then possibly Rfd1 and/or h3. We play in the center and on the Queenside (b2-b4) . A typical motif in combination with Rd1 is also exchanging on e5 and playing Nd2-e4 - heading for the d6-square. 2) Whenever Black plays ...h6, we go Bh4 (and possibly h3 and Bg3!) . 3) If Black plays ...c7-c5 at any moment, we play d5! with the deep positional threat of playing Nd2!. In this case, we would get a very good version of the Benoni and a clear advantage! } 6... c5 { If Black wants to play ...c5 he should do it when his knight is still on b8. He can include ...h6 however. } ( 6... h6 7. Bh4 g5 $5 { This is another playable though risky idea. Black creates long-term weaknesses on the Kingside! } ( 7... c5 8. d5 { --> 6...c5 } ) 8. Bg3 Nh5 { Now White has different options: } 9. Qc2 $5 ( 9. Be2 $5 c5 10. d5 { We almost always play d5 in response to ...c5.What happens after } 10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 { White has allowed Black to double his pawns but this is not a Nimzo Indian! White has good attacking possibilities. For instance } 11... Nd7 12. Nd2 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Kg7 14. f4 Nf6 15. e4 $14 { White has strong play in the center. } ) ( 9. Bd3 $5 ) 9... f5 10. Be2 Nxg3 ( 10... f4 11. exf4 gxf4 12. Bh4 $16 ) 11. hxg3 e5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. c5 $16 ) ( 6... Nbd7 7. Be2 h6 8. Bh4 c6 ( 8... c5 { should be played when the knight is still on b8. } 9. d5 $14 { Due to the knight being on d7 it's difficult to play . ..e6.For example } ( { With this concrete move order } 9. Qc2 $5 { is also interesting, e.g.The usual idea } 9... g5 ( 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 $14 ) 10. Bg3 Nh5 $2 { does not work due to the tactical shot } 11. Nxg5 $1 hxg5 12. Bxh5 $16 ) 9... g5 ( 9... b5 $6 10. cxb5 a6 11. O-O axb5 12. Bxb5 Ba6 13. a4 Bxb5 14. axb5 $14 { White's extra pawn may be double but it's not easy for Black to win it back or to obtain counterplay. } ) 10. Bg3 Nh5 11. Qc2 Nxg3 12. hxg3 Nf6 13. O-O ( 13. Nh2 ) 13... e6 14. dxe6 $1 ( 14. Rfd1 exd5 15. Nxd5 $14 ) 14... fxe6 15. Rad1 Qe7 16. Ne4 $16 ) 9. O-O e5 10. Qc2 $1 { This is a good alternative - with nice play in the center! If Black closes the center with ...e5-e4 at some moment, then we have very good play on the Queenside with a fast b2-b4! Let's look at some sample lines: } ( { White can also play the immediate } 10. h3 $1 { intending Bg3! } ) 10... Re8 { In such a situation we in general have three options: } ( 10... Qe8 11. h3 ( 11. Rfd1 ) ( 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nd2 ) 11... e4 $2 12. Nd2 d5 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Nb5 $18 ) ( 10... Qe7 11. h3 $1 ( 11. Rfd1 ) 11... e4 { This does not work so well. Black will not get an attack on the Kingside, while White's play on the Queenside develops very fast. } 12. Nd2 g5 13. Bg3 Re8 14. b4 $16 Nf8 15. c5 $1 { [%csl Gg3] White dark-squared bishop is very strong - it's a strong attacking and defending piece! } 15... d5 16. b5 $16 { For example } 16... h5 17. a4 ( 17. Qa4 ) 17... h4 18. Bd6 Qe6 19. a5 $18 ) 11. Rfd1 $14 { Keeping the tension. } ( 11. h3 $14 { Preparing Bg3. } 11... exd4 { in most cases we play } 12. Nxd4 { to keep the d-file open in order to attack d6. } 12... a5 13. Rad1 Nc5 14. Bf3 $14 { Controling e4 and preparing Bg3. } ( 14. b3 $14 ) ( 14. Rfe1 $14 ) ) ( 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nd2 $14 { Transferring the knight to e4. } ) ) ( 6... Bg4 $6 { A seemingly logical developing move but without a clear plan. } 7. Be2 { 7.h3 is also possible but I prefer to take back on f3 with the bishop. For instance } 7... Nbd7 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 c6 10. O-O e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Be2 Re8 13. Qc2 $16 { [%csl Rd6,Ge2,Gg5][%cal Yf1d1] Peacefully improving the position with a clear advantage. } ) ( 6... Bf5 $6 { Another random developing move. } 7. Bd3 $14 { Fighting for control over e4. Black does not get any counterplay. For example } 7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 h6 9. Bh4 $14 { For example } ( { or } 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. h4 $5 { with good prospects. } ) 9... Nbd7 10. O-O c6 11. Rfd1 Qe8 12. Qc2 e5 13. dxe5 $1 dxe5 14. Rd6 $16 { Even better than the traditional Nd2. White has strong pressure on the d-file. } ) 7. d5 $1 { Playing d5 is our answer to ...c5 in almost all cases. After this advance the positional threat is Nd2! REMEMBER: WE ONLY ARE THREATENING Nd2 IF OUR PAWN IS ON d5! I.e. after the pair of moves ...c5 and d5 have been played! } 7... h6 $1 { The only acceptable plan for Black is to go for ...g5, ...Nh5. He must do so BEFORE WE PLAY Nd2!, as afterward our queen controls h5 and it is too late! } ( 7... a6 8. a4 { Preventing a possible ...b5 just in case. } ( 8. Nd2 $5 e6 $2 9. Nde4 $16 { is very strong in this concrete position. } ( 9. Be2 $2 exd5 10. cxd5 b5 ) ( 9. a4 $16 exd5 10. cxd5 Nbd7 11. Be2 $16 { This is a very bad version of the Benoni for Black! Our bishop stands perfectly on h4! } 11... h6 12. Bh4 Re8 13. O-O Ne5 14. h3 $16 ( 14. a5 $16 ) ( 14. Qc2 $16 ) ) ) ) ( 7... Nbd7 $2 { A horrible move! Black will not manage to play ...e6 after this and remain without counterplay. } 8. Nd2 $16 { Again! Some sample lines: } 8... h6 ( 8... a6 9. a4 Ne5 10. Be2 Ne8 11. O-O h6 12. Bh4 g5 13. Bg3 f5 14. f4 gxf4 15. exf4 Ng4 16. Bxg4 fxg4 17. Bh4 Bxc3 18. bxc3 $16 ) 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 a6 11. a4 Qc7 12. Be2 { Black has no plan at all! If he tries ...e6, he might instantly get a losing position! } 12... e6 13. dxe6 $1 ( 13. O-O $16 exd5 14. cxd5 Re8 ( 14... Ne5 15. Bxe5 ( 15. f4 $16 ) 15... dxe5 16. Nc4 $16 ) 15. h3 Ne5 16. f4 gxf4 17. exf4 Ned7 18. f5 $18 ) 13... fxe6 14. h4 $18 ( 14. O-O $18 ) ) ( 7... e6 $2 8. Nd2 $16 exd5 9. cxd5 h6 10. Bh4 a6 ( 10... Na6 11. Be2 Nc7 12. O-O $14 { ...g5 is not a threat: } 12... g5 13. Bg3 Ncxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Ne4 $14 { winning back the pawn with advantage. } ) 11. a4 Nbd7 12. Be2 Re8 13. O-O $16 { THIS IS WHAT MOST OF YOUR OPPONENTS WILL PLAY! We get a very good version of the Benoni for White - with a clear advantage thanks to the powerful h4-bishop! } 13... Ne5 14. h3 Qc7 15. f4 Ned7 16. e4 $18 ) ( 7... Re8 $2 8. Nd2 $16 h6 9. Bh4 e6 ( 9... g5 { is too late now as Black no longer has ...Nh5. } 10. Bg3 $16 ) 10. Be2 exd5 11. cxd5 a6 12. a4 Nbd7 13. O-O Ne5 14. h3 g5 15. Bg3 Qe7 16. Bxe5 $16 ( 16. Ra3 $16 ) ( 16. Qc2 $16 Rb8 17. Rae1 ) 16... Qxe5 17. Nc4 Qe7 18. Nb6 Rb8 19. Qc2 Nd7 20. Nxc8 Rbxc8 ) ( 7... Qb6 $6 8. Rb1 Bf5 9. Bd3 $16 ) ( 7... Bg4 $2 { This is always totally pointless! } 8. Be2 Nbd7 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Bxf3 a6 ( 10... e6 $2 11. dxe6 fxe6 12. Qxd6 $18 ) 11. a4 $16 { For instance } 11... Ne5 12. Be2 Re8 13. O-O ( 13. f4 Ned7 14. O-O $18 ) 13... Qc7 14. f4 Ned7 15. e4 e5 16. f5 $18 ) 8. Bh4 g5 $1 ( 8... Na6 $6 9. Nd2 $14 { , for instance: } 9... e6 ( 9... e5 10. e4 Qe8 11. Be2 Nh7 12. g4 $16 { If Black plays ...f5, we capture two times. We get the open g-file and a nice square on e4 for our knights. } ) 10. Be2 exd5 11. cxd5 Nc7 12. O-O Re8 13. a4 b6 14. e4 $16 Rb8 15. f4 ) 9. Bg3 Nh5 10. Bd3 $14 ( 10. Qc2 $14 ) ( 10. Nd2 $14 Nxg3 11. hxg3 e6 12. Bd3 ( { or } 12. Qc2 { with the idea } 12... exd5 13. Nxd5 $14 ) 12... exd5 13. Nxd5 $36 Bxb2 $4 14. Rxh6 $18 ) 10... Nd7 ( 10... f5 $5 { This looks good but does in fact not threaten anything! } 11. Nd2 $1 ( 11. O-O $14 f4 12. exf4 Nxf4 13. Bxf4 Rxf4 14. Nd2 Nd7 15. Ne2 $3 Rf8 16. f4 $16 ) 11... Nxg3 12. hxg3 Nd7 ( 12... e6 13. g4 $14 ) ( 12... e5 13. e4 $3 f4 14. gxf4 $1 ( 14. Be2 $14 ) 14... exf4 ( 14... gxf4 15. Be2 $16 { [%cal Ye2g4] } ) ( 14... Rxf4 15. g3 Rf8 16. Be2 $16 ) 15. e5 $3 dxe5 16. Nde4 $16 { [%csl Ge4, Rg7] } ) 13. f4 $14 ) ( 10... Nxg3 11. hxg3 e6 ( 11... Na6 $4 12. Nxg5 $1 hxg5 13. Bh7+ $1 ( 13. Qh5 Re8 ) 13... Kh8 14. Qh5 $18 ) 12. Qc2 $5 ( 12. Bc2 $5 { --> see model game Akobian-Jaracz } ) 12... Na6 13. a3 exd5 14. Nxd5 Be6 15. Bh7+ $1 { A very important and very typical move, sending the king to the dangerous h- file! } 15... Kh8 16. Bf5 $16 ) ( 10... e6 11. Bc2 $14 ( 11. Qc2 $14 ) ) 11. Qc2 Ndf6 12. O-O Nxg3 13. hxg3 $14 { This line is probably the best Black can do. } *[Event "?"]
