1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bg5 { The game starts with the Torre Attack and later - after 7.c4 - transposes to the Smyslov System. } 3... Bg7 4. e3 O-O 5. Be2 d6 6. O-O b6 7. c4 Nbd7 8. Nc3 Bb7 9. Nd2 $14 ( 9. Qc2 $14 { Generally we must stop . ..Ne4. } ) 9... h6 10. Bh4 d5 $2 { After this Black's gets a very bad version of the Grünfeld! } 11. cxd5 ( 11. Bf3 $16 ) 11... Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Bf3 ( { Stronger was } 13. Qc2 $16 { , for instance } 13... Bb7 ( 13... c5 14. e4 Bb7 15. d5 $16 ) 14. b4 $16 ) 13... Bxf3 14. Nxf3 c5 15. Rc1 Rc8 $11 ( 15... cxd4 16. Nxd4 $14 { [%cal Yd4c6] } ) 16. Qe2 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Bxd4 19. exd4 { White accepted an isolated pawn but has some attacking chances as Black is missing his dark-squared bishop. } 19... Nf6 20. Rd1 ( 20. Bxf6 $5 exf6 21. Qc4 $14 ) 20... Qd7 ( 20... Nd5 $5 21. Qb5 Qd6 ) 21. Bxf6 exf6 22. d5 { White has the strong positional threat of pushing this passed pawn to d6. Black must prevent this! } 22... Qd6 $11 ( 22... Re8 23. Qd2 Qd6 $11 24. Qxh6 $2 Qxd5 $19 ) ( 22... Kg7 $2 23. d6 { Now there are several combinations possible. A sample line: } 23... Rc8 24. h3 Rc6 25. Qb5 Kf8 $2 26. Qxc6 $1 Qxc6 27. d7 $18 ) 23. Qa6 Re8 24. h3 Re7 25. Qd3 Kg7 26. a3 a5 27. Qc4 Rc7 28. Qd3 h5 29. h4 Re7 30. g3 Rc7 31. Kg2 Re7 32. Qc4 Rc7 33. Qd4 Rd7 34. Rd3 Rc7 35. Rc3 Rc5 36. Rxc5 bxc5 37. Qe4 f5 38. Qd3 Kf6 39. Kf3 Ke5 40. Qc3+ Kxd5 41. Qb3+ Ke5 42. Qxf7 Qc6+ 43. Ke3 Qe4+ 44. Kd2 Qd4+ 45. Ke1 Qe4+ 46. Kd2 Qd4+ 47. Ke1 Qe4+ 1/2-1/2[Event "Titled Tuesday 16th Feb"]
