1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nf3 O-O 5. Bg5 d6 6. e3 c5 7. Be2 { This is playable too but our move is 7.d5! } 7... h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Bg3 Nh5 10. d5 $1 Nxg3 11. hxg3 e6 12. Nd2 ( 12. Qc2 $14 exd5 13. Nxd5 $1 ) ( 12. Nh2 $36 ) 12... exd5 13. Nxd5 $1 ( 13. cxd5 f5 $13 ) 13... Nc6 ( 13... Bxb2 $2 14. Rxh6 $18 ) 14. Ne4 $1 Re8 15. Nec3 { White has stabilized his position and is better. } 15... a6 16. O-O Be6 ( 16... f5 17. Qd2 ) 17. Rb1 ( 17. Qd2 { followed by Rad1 was simpler. } ) 17... Rb8 18. a3 Ne7 19. b4 { Not the best plan. } 19... b5 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Nd5 Qb7 ( 21... Bxd5 22. Qxd5 { White is better due to the weaknesses of the light squares in Black's camp. } ) 22. Bf3 $1 ( 22. bxc5 $6 dxc5 $15 ) ( 22. Qd2 $2 { is a positional mistake - White must be ready to take back on d5 with a piece. } 22... Bxd5 23. cxd5 { Probably the better practical chance - with queens on the board White can hope for some attacking possibilities. } ( 23. Qxd5 Qxd5 24. cxd5 c4 $17 ) 23... c4 $17 { [%cal Ye2g4,Yg4f5,Yf2f4] } ) 22... Qc8 ( 22... Qd7 $11 ) 23. Rc1 $14 Bd7 24. Qd2 bxc4 25. Be2 Be6 26. Bxc4 { After some inaccuracies, White is again seriously better. His pieces are excellent and even exchanging the d5-knight does not help Black. } 26... Qb7 27. Rfd1 Qa7 28. Rb1 Rec8 29. Qd3 Rc6 30. Rbc1 Kf8 31. a4 cxb4 32. Nxb4 Rxb4 33. Bxe6 Qc7 34. Rxc6 Qxc6 35. Qf5 Rb7 36. Bd5 Qd7 37. Qf3 $1 { White of course keeps the queens on the board as the opponent's king is unsafe. } 37... Rc7 38. Rb1 Qc8 39. Kh2 Be5 40. Bb7 Qd7 41. a5 Qa4 42. Be4 Qd7 43. Bd3 Kg7 44. Qe4 f5 45. Qa8 Qf7 46. Qf3 h5 47. Kg1 Kh6 48. Bxa6 f4 49. gxf4 gxf4 50. exf4 Qxf4 51. Qxf4+ Bxf4 52. Bb7 Rc5 53. a6 Ra5 54. g3 Be5 55. Rd1 Kg7 56. f4 Bf6 57. Rxd6 Be7 58. Rd5 Ra3 59. Kh2 Kg6 60. Re5 Bf6 61. Be4+ Kh6 62. Re6 Kg7 63. Rd6 1-0[Event "chess.com INT"]
