{ The most amazing and instructive game by White!! } 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. c4 Bg7 4. Nc3 O-O 5. Bg5 d6 6. e3 c5 7. d5 Na6 $6 { Everyone allows Nd2!, because this is a very very deep positional trap! } 8. Nd2 Nc7 9. a4 Rb8 ( 9... Na6 10. Be2 Nb4 { The black knight looks nice but does not take part in the fight for the center and has in fact no moves. For example } 11. O-O e6 12. e4 exd5 13. cxd5 Re8 14. f3 ( 14. f4 ) 14... a6 15. Nc4 Qc7 16. Qd2 $16 ) 10. Be2 a6 11. a5 $16 ( 11. e4 $5 ) 11... b5 12. axb6 Rxb6 13. Ra2 Qe8 14. e4 e6 15. O-O h6 16. Bf4 e5 17. Be3 Nd7 18. g4 $3 { White wants to stop ...f5 at all cost. Then he intends to close the Kingside! Study this amazing game very deeply! } 18... Qe7 19. Kh1 $3 Kh7 20. Nf3 Bf6 21. Qd2 Rg8 22. Rg1 g5 23. h4 Nf8 24. h5 $18 { After executing his strategic goal (i.e. closing the Kingside - a typical idea in the King's Indian) , White will slowly win on the Queenside! } 24... Bd7 25. Ne1 Qd8 26. Nd3 Qb8 27. Rb1 Rb7 28. Bd1 Bd8 29. f3 Bc8 30. Ne2 a5 31. Rxa5 Nce6 32. Ra2 Nf4 33. Nec1 Nd7 34. b3 Bb6 35. Rba1 Nf6 36. Nf2 Qc7 37. Ne2 Bd7 38. Ng3 Ra7 39. Rxa7 Bxa7 40. Ra6 Rb8 41. Qa2 Bb6 42. Bd2 Qb7 43. Bc3 Bc8 44. Ra3 Ne8 45. Kg1 Nc7 46. Nf5 Bxf5 47. exf5 Ncxd5 48. cxd5 Qxd5 49. Qd2 c4 50. Qxd5 Nxd5 51. bxc4 Bc5 52. cxd5 Bxa3 53. Ba4 Bc5 54. Kf1 Ra8 55. Bc6 Ra2 56. Ne4 Ba3 57. Ke1 Kg7 58. f6+ Kf8 59. Kd1 Rh2 60. Ba5 Kg8 61. Ke1 Ra2 62. Bc7 Bb4+ 63. Kf1 Ra1+ 64. Ke2 Ra2+ 65. Ke3 Ra3+ 66. Kf2 Ra2+ 67. Kg3 Re2 68. Kh3 Kh7 69. Bb5 Re1 70. Kg2 Kg8 71. Nxd6 Rc1 72. Bc6 Rc2+ 73. Kf1 Rc1+ 74. Ke2 Rc2+ 75. Kd3 Rf2 76. Ke3 Bc5+ 77. Ke4 Re2+ 78. Kd3 Re3+ 79. Kc4 Ba3 80. Nb5 Bb2 81. d6 e4 82. Bxe4 Bxf6 83. d7 1-0[Event "30th ECC Open 2014"]
